<DATE_TIME> 1996-07-21 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> French Company Rejects Reports of Child Labor in Myanmar </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PARIS, July 20 (Xinhua) -- The French energy group Total has
rejected reports that the group is exploiting child labor in a gas
field in Yadana, Myanmar.
</P>
<P>
In an interview with the French daily Le Monde published for
its Sunday-Monday edition, Daniel Valot, general director of the
Exploration and Production Department of Total, said that there
are no children in the gas field.
</P>
<P>
He said the television report, made by the British ITV channel
belonging to Carlton UK and shown on television in several
European countries in May, is inconsistent between its commentary
and picture, and Total is "the victim of a persistent and
malicious campaign of disinformation."
</P>
<P>
"The pictures were taken in a construction site which is not
ours," said Valot, adding that reporters and human rights groups
are welcome to see for themselves in Myanmar whether Total employs
children or not.
</P>
<P>
He said that the company employs 500-600 local adult men and
women during the drought season there, has built a medical network
for local villages, helps develop local cattle trade and help
eradicate the malaria epidemic there.
</P>
<P>
Valot said that Total is not the only company joining the
project and the American company Unocal, the Thai company PTT-EP
and the Myanmar company MOGE also have investment in the project
which totals 1 billion U.S. dollars.
</P>
<P>
The gas field, the biggest energy project in Myanmar which is
developed to provide energy to neighboring Thailand, is expected
to start producing gas in 1998, and making profits by 2002, he
said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
