<HEADLINE> 300 Soldiers killed in Mullaitivu Fighting: Military </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
COLOMBO, July 21 (Xinhua) -- Around 300 government soldiers
have been killed and over 200 others injured during the recent
Tamil rebel attack on the Mullaitivu army base in the northeastern
coast of Sri Lanka, according to a military news release issued
tonight.
</P>
<P>
However, the release said that the exact number killed or
wounded cannot be ascertained yet due to the difficulty in
communicating with the troops at Mullaitivu town.
</P>
<P>
Tamil rebel transmissions monitored so far indicated that over
400 rebels were killed and a large number injured, the release
said.
</P>
<P>
The Sri Lankan navy was able to ferry a large number of fresh
troops today to strengthen the troops advancing towards
Mullaitivu. The first such group was beach landed at 14:30 hours
today. The Sri Lankan Air Force provided close air support to
ensure safety of the troops while landing.
</P>
<P>
The release said that operation code named "Thrivida Pahara"
(three sides attack) was launched on July 18 with the aim of
providing assistance to troops who came under the Tamil rebel
attack on the Mullaitivu base.
</P>
<P>
Initially troops of the special forces were landed three to
four kilometers south of Mullaitivu in order to secure a beach
head. As reported earlier these troops came under the enemy's
fire, resulting in a delay in advancing towards the Mullaitivu
base, said the release, adding that the Sri Lankan air force
continued to provide fire support to the reinforcing troops.
</P>
</TEXT>
