<BODY>
<HEADLINE> French FM to Start Mideast Tour Monday </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PARIS, July 21 (Xinhua) -- French Foreign Minister Herve de
Charette Monday will begin a three-day visit to the Middle East to
renew the peace process which has stalled since Israel's
right-wing forces came to power at the end of May.
</P>
<P>
De Charette, who will visit Damascus, Beirut, Jerusalem, the
Gaza Strip, Amman and Cairo, will be the first foreign minister
from a European Union country to visit Israel since Bejamin
Netanyahu came to power.
</P>
<P>
However, de Charette's first meeting with Israeli Prime
Minister Netanyahu is overshadowed by the dispute over whether the
foreign minister should visit the East House, the official seat of
the Palestine Liberation Organization in East Jerusalem.
</P>
<P>
France has insisted on the freedom to travel to East Jerusalem,
while the Israeli government has recently increased pressure on
East House, indicating that it is studying measures to ban senior
foreign officials from visiting the place.
</P>
<P>
"We will not give in to pressure (from Israel). The minister
will do what is considered to be worth to do," Foreign Ministry
officials said last Friday.
</P>
<P>
De Charette said that he would carry no prejudice against
anyone, but will be firm on the point that the commitments already
made by both sides of the Mideast should be taken into action.
</P>
<P>
He said that he will also remind the leaders of the Mideast
countries that the enemies of peace will take advantage of the
present deadlock.
</P>
<P>
The commitments, made between former Israeli Prime Ministers
Yitzak Rabin and Shimon Peres and Arab leaders, have been
jeopardized by the intransigent stance of Netanyahu, who succeeded
in silencing criticism from Egyptian President Hosni Mubarak but
made no concession during his latest visit to Cairo.
</P>
<P>
De Charette's visit coincides with one by U.S. coordinator for
Mideast peace process Dennis Ross, who will also be in the Mideast
Monday.
</P>
<P>
The Agence France Presse (AFP) said that the parallel visits by
de Charette and Ross could lead to another Franco-U.S. rivalry in
mediating peace talks in the region.
</P>
<P>
France and the United States have competed in arranging a
ceasefire after Israel launched raids against Hezbollah guerillas
in south Lebanon and Beirut in April.
</P>
<P>
Nevertheless, France-U.S. diplomatic cooperation at that time
led to the establishment of a monitoring committee of ceasefire in
south Lebanon, which will hold its first session on July 25.
</P>
<P>
The committee, consisting representatives from Israel, Syria
and Lebanon besides France and the United States, will be a place
to test whether Paris and Washington can work hand in hand on the
Mideast, said the AFP. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
