<P>
KATHMANDU -- A workers' union of the state-run Nepal Telecom
Corporation (NTC) Sunday called off a major strike in protest of
the government's policy to privatize the country's telecom
industry.
</P>
<P>
LONDON -- Britain is now the most unequal country in the
Western world with an increasingly widening gap between the rich
and poor, said a United Nations report carried in the Sunday Times
newspaper.
</P>
<P>
ISLAMABAD -- On the advice of Afghan Prime Minister Gulbuddin
Hekmatyar, President Burhanuddin Rabbani Sunday appointed
Qutbuddin Helal, one of Hekmatyar's top political officers, as
deputy premier, according to a report from Kabul.
</P>
<P>
KAFR TIBNIT, Lebanon -- Seventeen prisoners of the militia of
the South Lebanese Army set free by Hezbollah arrived here as part
of the swap of prisoners and remains between Hezbollah and Israel
in 14 years.
</P>
<P>
JAKARTA -- The inaugural Ministerial Conference of the World
Trade Organization (WTO) will be held in Singapore in December
this year, foreign ministers of the Association of Southeast Asian
Nations (ASEAN) said at a two-day meeting ending here Sunday.
</P>
<P>
AMMAN -- Drug trafficking is becoming rampant in Jordan, which
is usually used as a transit point for narcotics smuggled from
Syria, Lebanon, Turkey and Egypt.  The Public Security Department
announced in a statement released Saturday that, in the second
major round-up of alleged drug trafficking rings in the kingdom in
July, its Anti-Narcotics Unit arrested a total of 35 suspects in
three separate attempts at drug trafficking through Jordanian
territory in the past 10 days.
</P>
<P>
JERUSALEM -- Israeli Army decided Sunday to freeze the action
of easing the closure on Palestinian territories, in an effort to
force the Palestinian police to release an abducted Israeli
citizen. 
</P>
