<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Growing New Jobs Are Good Ones in U.S.--New York Times </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW YORK, July 21 (Xinhua) -- A rising share of new jobs in the
United States have paid more than average since 1992, the New York
Times reported today.
</P>
<P>
After years of downsizings of companies, many Americans have
worried about their earnings. But millions of them have found in
the past five years that new jobs more than replace the lost ones,
according to the paper.
</P>
<P>
Earlier reports said that people usually got less pay in new
jobs. But it is not the situation, according to a set of
government figures of the past five years about the changes in
jobs and earnings. It said 25 percent of the new jobs in 1995 paid
at least 30 percent more than the national average income, which
was 29,420 U.S. dollars.
</P>
<P>
About 45 percent of the jobs created across the country last
year paid more than the national average wage of 29,420 U.S.
dollars. In 1992, that proportion was just 22 percent. Of the new
jobs created last year, fully one-quarter paid more than 30
percent above the average. In 1992, only 4 percent of the new jobs
paid that well.
</P>
<P>
These jumps are encouraging, the paper said, considering that
many new jobs, such as Internet, are for young people just
entering the work force, and they typically earn less than
experienced workers.
</P>
<P>
The paper also said that the economy is churning out better
jobs than many Americans might think.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
