<DATE_TIME> 1996-07-21 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Jewish Students Banned From Commemoration in French City </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PARIS, July 21 (Xinhua) -- A dozen Jewish students in the
southern city of Toulon today were banned from joining a local
commemoration of the rounding-up of Jews in the Velodrome d'Hiver
in Paris on July 16, 1942.
</P>
<P>
The commemoration was jointly organized by the Prefecture of
Val and the Municipality of Toulon, which is run by a mayor from
the ultra-rightist Front National (FN) party, the Agence France
Presse (AFP) reported.
</P>
<P>
AFP quoted prefecture officials as saying that the students
were banned because they carried boards with letters of "Former
collaborators, Members of FN."
</P>
<P>
"Fifty-four years after the rounding up of Jews in Velodrome
d'Hiver, it is illogical to observe that the Jewish students of
France are considered as second class citizens," said Yariv
Abshsera, president of the Union of Jewish Students of France.
</P>
<P>
The commemoration was presided over by Val prefect Jean Charles
Marchiani, but Toulon's FN mayor Jean-Marie Le Chevallier did not
attend.
</P>
<P>
French police rounded up 13,000 Jews on July 16, 1942, in
Velodrome d'Hiver of Paris and then transported them to Nazi death
camps.
</P>
<P>
The event represented one of the darkest pages of the history
of the Vichy collaboration period in France from 1940 to 1944.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
