<DOCNO> XIE19960721.0029 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1996-07-21 14:27 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Syrian President Meets Egyptian FM </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DAMASCUS, July 21 (Xinhua) -- Syrian President Hafez al-Assad
met today with Egyptian Foreign Minister Amr Moussa in Syria's
port city of Latakia.
</P>
<P>
During the meeting, which was attended by Syrian Foreign
Minister Farouq al-Shara, Moussa briefed President al-Assad on the
outcome of the talks held between Egyptian President Hosni Mubarak
and Israeli Prime Minister Benjamin Netanyahu in Cairo Thursday,
reliable Syrian sources said.
</P>
<P>
The two discussed the developments in the Middle East region
and the recent contacts made by both Syria and Egypt at the Arab
and international levels.
</P>
<P>
Assad and Moussa also held talks on ways of developing the
outcome of the recent Cairo Arab summit and boosting Arab joint
action so that a fair and overall peace can be established in the
region, the sources said.
</P>
<P>
Moussa arrived in Latakia this morning for a visit to
Syria.
</P>
<P>
Netanyahu visited Cairo Thursday, his first visit to an Arab
country after his victory in Israel's May 29 elections. His public
remarks in Cairo appeared to signal a softer Israeli approach
toward future Arab-Israel peace moves.
</P>
<P>
But Syria said that Netanyahu's statements in Cairo have failed
to clearly affirm his commitment to the land-for-peace principle,
on which the Middle East peace process was based.
</P>
<P>
The English-language daily Syria Times said today that Damascus
would not resume peace talks with Israel unless the Jewish state
pledged to return to its control the Golan Heights, a strategic
plateau Israel captured from Syria in the 1967 Middle East war.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19960721.0030 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1996-07-21 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Vietnamese Banks Urged to Lend More </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HANOI, July 21 (Xinhua) -- Vietnam will extend the lending
ceilings of its commercial banks to encourage them lending more to
Vietnamese businesses, the Vietnam News Agency (VNA) reported
today.
</P>
<P>
Le Van Chau, deputy governor of Vietnam's central bank, the
State Bank, was quoted by (VNA) as saying that the central bank
will also give priority to long and mid-term loans.
</P>
<P>
The move by the central bank is aimed at cutting the huge "dead
lending capital" in the commercial banks of the country, estimated
at 10,000 billion dong (nearly 1 billion U.S. dollars), VNA said.
</P>
<P>
The bank will work together with the Ministry of Finance to
regularly open treasury bill biddings and issue state bank bonds
aimed at regulating capital sources among commercial banks, the
deputy governor said.
</P>
<P>
He disclosed that loans given by Vietnamese banks account for
only 60 to 70 percent of their usable capital.
</P>
<P>
By the end of May, some commercial banks were still yet to use
the credit ceilings set for 1996 by the State Bank, he said.
</P>
<P>
Sources at the commercial banks, however, do not agree. They
argued that stagnation in the capital lending market has been
caused by low lending limits set by the State Bank.
</P>
<P>
They also complained that commercial banks could not put their
idle money to use by increasing investment in businesses, as
Vietnamese laws impose limits on the proportion of bank investment
in enterprises.
</P>
<P>
VNA said it is a paradox that while large amounts of money
remains idle in banks, many businesses are badly in need of
capital to purchase advanced technical equipment for long-term
development.
</P>
<P>
At least both sides agree that the present interest rates of
bank loans are too high, averaging 21 percent a year.
</P>
<P>
The current lending regulations is too harsh and complicated,
often beyond the capacity of businesses, VNA said, for instance,
to get bank loans, a business must hold at least 30 percent of its
total investment, and have enough property to mortgage.
</P>
<P>
VNA said many businesses, especially private companies, do not
fulfill bank lending regulations. At present, only 5 percent of
Vietnam's private businesses have access to bank loans.
</P>
<P>
Another reason for the lending capital surplus at Vietnamese
banks is that domestic businesses have borrowed an estimated total
of 1 billion U.S. dollars from foreign banks, who offer lower
interest rates and longer repayment terms than Vietnamese banks.
</P>
<P>
By offering annual interest rates of only 7 percent, many
foreign banks are luring domestic customers away from Vietnamese
banks, and placing domestic banks in an untenable situation, VNA
said. 
</P>
