<HEADLINE> Transnational Firms Swarm to Shanghai </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SHANGHAI, July 21 (Xinhua) -- Fifty-five transnational firms
have poured heavy investments into Shanghai, the largest economic
center of China.
</P>
<P>
Among those companies swarming to the investment hot spot this
year are the US Philip Morris Company, Germany's Robert Bosch
GmbH, and Japan's Nippon Electric Co., Ltd. (NEC).
</P>
<P>
So far, nearly 200 of the world's top industrial enterprises
have committed investment in Shanghai, covering automobile,
telecommunications, light industry, instruments and chemical
industries.
</P>
<P>
More than 40 percent of the output value of local leading
industries are generated by the foreign-funded enterprises in the
city.
</P>
<P>
The 55 transnational firms have developed 85 projects in the
Pudong New Area, which has become the city's most attractive and
multi-functional area. Japan's Yaohan International Group is
resettling its headquarters in Pudong.
</P>
<P>
In order to encourage more transnational firms to invest in the
city, local authorities have taken effective measures to improve
its investment environment.
</P>
<P>
The Shanghai Pudong Development Bank has granted large loans
for some transnational firms to help expand their business in
Shanghai. 
</P>
