<HEADLINE> Prince William Suggested to Open Sydney 2000 Games </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CANBERRA, July 21 (Xinhua) -- Australian Deputy Prime Minister
Tim Fischer said today that he would be happy to see the Queen
open the Sydney 2000 Olympics, but suggested Prince William might
be appropriate.
</P>
<P>
Speaking at the "Meet the Press" program in TV Ten Network,
Fischer said "Yesterday's Olympic Games opening ceremony failed to
properly show aspects of American or Greek culture, and Sydney's
effort in four years' time should combine Australian culture and
Olympic razzmatazz."
</P>
<P>
In this context, he said Prince William -- second in line to
the British throne behind his father Prince Charles -- might be
appropriate, "perhaps Prince William should try his hand."
</P>
<P>
His remarks immediately renewed debate on the issue of the
Australian republic, the federal oppositions, Democrats and
Republicans condemned the suggestion by Fischer.
</P>
<P>
Australian Republican Movement Chairman Malcolm Turnbull said
he was astonished by the idea, "the Olympic Games are opened by
the Head of State of the host country, that is why President
Clinton declared the Games open in Atlanta yesterday."
</P>
<P>
A spokesman of the Labor Party said, his party believes the
Sydney Olympics should be opened by the Australian head of state.
"We hope by that time the Australian people will have been given
an opportunity to express an opinion on whether our head of state
should be an Australian."
</P>
<P>
Australian Democrats leader Cheryl Kernot also opposed the
Fischer's idea and expressed that the Democrats would campaign in
a referendum for Australia becoming a republic.
</P>
<P>
So far as the ruling coalition is concerned, although many of
them support the monarchy, they also agreed to hold a referendum
to decide whether Australia should become a republic, however,
they would hold a people's convention ahead of the referendum with
half of the members of the convention appointed by the coalition.
 
</P>
</TEXT>
