<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Han Prince's Remains Unearthed in Jiangsu </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NANJING, July 21 (Xinhua) -- Complete skeletal remains of a
prince who lived during the early Han Dynasty (206 BC-220 AD) have
been unearthed from a lacquer coffin decorated with more than
1,600 pieces of jade.
</P>
<P>
The coffin was found in a large tomb, where China's most
precious jade robe was unearthed earlier.
</P>
<P>
Chinese archaeologists were surprised that the skeleton had
remained intact for 2,100 years. They said that the prince, Liu
Wu, was 1.72 m tall and died when he was about 35.
</P>
<P>
Experts have sculpted a likeness of the prince, who has a
strong, wide lower jaw and is said to appear arrogant.
</P>
<P>
Historical records show that Liu, Prince of Chu of the third
generation, united with six other princes to fight against the Han
emperor, his cousin.
</P>
<P>
Liu was defeated and committed suicide. However, he was buried
with honors in a 117 m long, 13.2 m wide tomb, dug deep into Mount
Lion in present-day Xuzhou, in east China's Jiangsu Province, the
site of his fiefdom.
</P>
<P>
Experts say that it took at least twenty years to build the
tomb.
</P>
<P>
The tomb was robbed soon after it was completed, but it still
contained 1,500 objects of gold, silver, bronze, iron, jade,
pottery, and lacquer, plus nearly 100 pieces of weaponry, 176,000
copper coins and 200 official seals.
</P>
<P>
Experts place the highest value on the jade, including the jade
coffin and jade robe, which were made of highest quality stone
from Hetian in northwest China's Xinjiang Uygur Autonomous Region.
</P>
<P>
Excavation of the tomb began in 1994, and is continuing.
</P>
<P>
Chinese archaeologists are now trying to find the chamber that
contains the remains of Liu's wife. Princes who lived during the
Han Dynasty were buried with their wives and a unique scent,
probably from the wife's chamber, can be smelled in tomb, they
said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
