<DATE_TIME> 1996-07-21 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Fossilized Human Skulls, Bone Ware Found in Stone Age Cave </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
GUIYANG, July 21 (Xinhua) -- Two fossilized human skulls,
nearly 1,000 utensils made from bone, and traces of fire have been
discovered in Chuandong Cave, about 120 km from this capital of
southwest China's Guizhou Province.
</P>
<P>
Chinese experts says that the skulls, which date back 8,000
years, are the first from that time period ever found in south
China. The bone items, which scientists say are older than the
skulls, dispel the long-held belief that boneware was non-existent
in China in the late Paleolithic Age.
</P>
<P>
About 18,000 animal bone fragments and 500 teeth were also
found in the cave.
</P>
<P>
Relics from the cave date from 16,000 to 8,000 years ago,
indicating that the history of human beings living in the region
can be traced back that far, experts say.
</P>
<P>
Experts say that the cave, 30 m long, 13 m wide and nine m
high, is warm in winter and cool in summer, and offered favorable
living conditions for the ancient residents.
</P>
<P>
The cave was discovered in 1978 and has been listed among 500
historical sites under state protection. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
