<HEADLINE> Israeli Soldiers' Remains Return Home in Swap Deal with </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, July 21 (Xinhua) -- A German military plane carrying
the bodies of two Israeli soldiers died in 1986 in south Lebanon
arrived at Tel Aviv today in a German-brokered swap deal between
Israel and Hezbollah.
</P>
<P>
The remains of Yosef Fink and Rahamim Alsheikh were
immediately transferred to the Israeli Army's chief rabbi for
identification check when the plane arrived this morning at the
Ben-Gurion Airport from Lebanon.
</P>
<P>
Israel Radio reported that the bodies of the two Israeli
soldiers were firstly handed over to the Red Cross in Beirut, and
then over to German mediator Bernd Schmidbauer.
</P>
<P>
Fink and Alsheikh were abducted in 1986 in an ambush by the
Hezbollah forces in south Lebanon. The two later died in
captivity. Several previous efforts to secure return of the two's
bodies failed before the latest efforts launched by the German
team.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Israeli Army handed over more than 100 bodies of
slain Hezbollah soldiers to the Red Cross in a south Lebanon
village, which will be transferred to the Hezbollah.
</P>
<P>
And, as the second part of the swap deal, the Israeli side
released 45 Hezbollah prisoners in exchange for 17 South Lebanon
Army soldiers captured by Hezbollah.
</P>
<P>
Mediator Schmidbauer, a top intelligence adviser to German
Chancellor Helmut Kohl, said that it took him three months
to secure the swap deal.
</P>
<P>
Israeli Prime Minister Benjamin Netanyahu is to meet with
Schmidbauer this afternoon to discuss the whereabouts of other
Israeli soldiers missing in action. It is hoped that the swap
will lead to a bigger deal in the future.
</P>
<P>
Israeli President Ezer Weizman welcomed the exchange as a
relief for the families of the two soldiers, who have
suffered long pains and sorrows. He added that, despite the
anger against "enemies", "there are also mothers waiting in
the other side."




