<HEADLINE> Relief Food Sent to Refugee Camp in N. Uganda </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, July 21 (Xinhua) -- The World Food Program (WFP) sent
emergency food aid to Acholpi refugee camp in northern Uganda --
the first relief food to arrive at the beleaguered camp since a
bloody rebel attack over a week ago.
</P>
<P>
A WFP release issued here today said the U. N. food aid agency
sent five trucks carrying 80 tons of food to Acholpi camp on June
15, and they pulled into Lira, some 90 kms from Acholpi the next
day and arrived at the camp this morning after the convoy
received security clearance.
</P>
<P>
Acholpi camp is home to some 16,000 refugees from southern
Sudan and the food delivered can cater for them for a period of
two weeks, said the release.
</P>
<P>
Ugandan rebels attacked Acholpi camp on July 12 and 13,
killing more than 100 refugees and burning down 335 makeshift
homes in "most horrific assaults on refugees ever in the region."
</P>
<P>
WFP's convoys are usually escorted by soldiers to northern
Uganda because rebels attacks would occur at any time.
</P>
<P>
On July 4, rebels ambushed 11 WFP trucks returning from
northern Uganda, killing several people and burning four trucks.
Two Ugandan nationals hired were killed in the raid.
</P>
<P>
Civil war forced Sudanese refugees to flee to northern Uganda
and they began arriving in the districts of Moyo, Arua, Masindi
and Kitgum in 1988. WFP has been providing food to 216,000
southern Sudanese living in refugee camps and settlements there
since. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
