<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China Vows to Wipe out Iodine Deficiency Diseases </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, July 21 (Xinhua) -- China has vowed to eliminate its
alarming occurrence of iodine deficiency diseases (IDD) in the
next few years, according to a health official.
</P>
<P>
"Over 80 percent of Chinese have now used iodized salt and all
the people in areas prone to the endemic goiter and cretinism have
access to iodized salt," said Vice-Minister of Public Health Yin
Dakui, after hearing a report from the United Nations officials.
</P>
<P>
The UN delegation conducted a 15-day assessment and discussion
of the country's international cooperation projects for
elimination of IDD by the year 2000.
</P>
<P>
Aided by the World Bank, China has built a 980-million yuan
project for salt iodization, he said.
</P>
<P>
"It is a tough task for a country with a population of 1.2
billion people to spread in a long run the standard iodized salt,"
the official said.
</P>
<P>
This task is even more difficult in the 592 poverty-stricken
counties with 65 million inhabitants, he said.
</P>
<P>
China is one of the countries in the world with severe IDD
prevalence.
</P>
<P>
The goal of the Chinese government is to make all salt in the
country iodized by 1996, and to eliminate IDD nationwide by the
year 2000. 
</P>
</TEXT>
