<HEADLINE> New Technique Means Ten Billion Kg More Wheat for China </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HUHHOT, July 21 (Xinhua) -- A new technique of using plastic
film for growing wheat, developed by the Gansu Provincial Academy
of Agricultural Sciences, is expected to increase the country's
wheat output by up to 10 billion kg at the turn of the century,
according to Chinese scientists.
</P>
<P>
The technique of applying plastic film throughout the growing
period has been used on more than 40,000 ha of land in Gansu,
Inner Mongolia, Ningxia, Xinjiang and Shanxi. Experiments show
that the method increased output by more than 30 percent.
</P>
<P>
According to scientists, the technique means a breakthrough for
wheat output. China plans to apply it to more than six million ha
of land by the turn of the century, a move expected to increase
the country's wheat output by between 7.5 and 10 billion kg, a
figure which might account for up to half of China's planned wheat
increase during the Ninth Five-year Plan period (1996-2000).
</P>
<P>
China grows nearly 30 million ha of wheat annually, on 28
percent of its total crop growing area, with an annual output of
ten billion kg, or 21 percent of the national grain output. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
