<DATE_TIME> 1996-07-21 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Diabetic Children Increase in Shanghai </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, July 21 (Xinhua) -- The number of diabetic children in
China is increasing, with 350 cases reported in Shanghai in the
past decade.
</P>
<P>
Of the figure, 150 were from Shanghai and 200 from other cities
and provinces, according to a survey conducted by professor Chen
Shuixian, at the Children's Hospital of Shanghai Medical
University.
</P>
<P>
The "China Women's News" quoted Chen as saying that the young
patients, aged usually from nine to 13 years old, mostly suffer
from insulin-dependent diabetes.
</P>
<P>
The survey showed that almost no children suffered from
diabetes before the 1980s, the paper said.
</P>
<P>
The major causes for the increase of diabetes among children
probably stem from environmental problems, viral infections,
unbalanced diets, weak immune systems and genetics, Chen said.
</P>
<P>
Scientists warned that parents should supervise their
children's diets to prevent them from becoming overweight. 
</P>
</TEXT>
