<HEADLINE> Nigerian Versity Loses W. Bank Offer </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, July 21 (xinhua) -- Nigeria's University of Ibadan has
lost a multi-million-dollar World Bank-Japan graduate scholarship
program to Ghana's Legon University because of its declining
standards and dilapidating structures.
</P>
<P>
The graduate program in economics, jointly funded by the World
Bank and Japan, is to sponsor two African universities, one each
from east and west Africa, the Sunday Tribune newspaper reported
today.
</P>
<P>
The beneficiaries are selected in six candidates -- the
University of Ibadan and Legon University in west Africa and four
others in east Africa, including the University of Nairobi in
Kenya.
</P>
<P>
A selection committee set up by the sponsors started visiting
the six universities in 1992 and finished its work last December
when it submitted its report to the sponsors.
</P>
<P>
In the evaluation subdivided into various sections, the report
rated the admission requirements of both Ibadan and Legon
universities as satisfactory. But the library facilities of
Ibadan University are poorer than those in Legon University, and
so is the case in the area of computer facilities.
</P>
<P>
On physical infrastructure, the report said in Ibadan
''conditions are poor. Buildings are deteriorating for lack of
proper maintenance and management, while in Ghana conditions are
acceptable though facilities are not as comprehensive as in
Ibadan.''
</P>
<P>
The University of Ibadan is also rated low in areas of
accommodation availability and cost, security and health,
academic staff and foreign students taken in. 
</P>
</TEXT>
