<DATE_TIME> 1996-07-21 09:24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Drug Trafficking Rampant in Jordan </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
AMMAN, July 21 (Xinhua) -- Drug trafficking is becoming
rampant in Jordan, which is usually used as a transit point for
narcotics smuggled from Syria, Lebanon, Turkey and Egypt.
</P>
<P>
The Public Security Department (PSD) announced in a statement
released Saturday that, in the second major round-up of alleged
drug trafficking rings in the kingdom in July, its Anti-Narcotics
Unit arrested a total of 35 suspects in three separate attempts at
drug trafficking through Jordanian territory in the past 10 days.
</P>
<P>
The statement disclosed that from July 10 to 20, the PSD has
seized 159 kilograms of hashish on the northern borders with Syria.
</P>
<P>
More than 31,000 drug tablets, 17 kilograms of hashish and 1
kilogram of hashish oil were seized in the same period in two
other operations in the northeast.
</P>
<P>
The intensified anti-narcotics campaigns throughout the kingdom
were undertaken under the directives of Prime Minister Abdul
Karim Kabariti.
</P>
<P>
On July 10, the PSD said that it has arrested, during the
period from July 1 to 10 when the first major round-up was
launched, a group of traffickers and seized 67 kilograms of
hashish, 4.5 kilograms of heroin and a large quantity of other
drugs allegedly smuggled from a neighboring Arab country and
destined for another.
</P>
<P>
The two massive operations underlined what officials describe
as the most intensive trafficking activity in the Middle East
in two decades.
</P>
<P>
The PSD seized a record amount of more than three tons
of smuggled narcotics last year. 
</P>
</TEXT>
