<HEADLINE> ASEAN Hails Progress Towards Establishment of AFTA </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JAKARTA, July 21 (Xinhua) -- Much progress has been made
towards the establishment of the ASEAN Free Trade Area (AFTA),
said a joint communique issued at the end of the 29th ASEAN
Ministerial Meeting (AMM) here today.
</P>
<P>
Foreign ministers of the Association of Southeast Asian Nations
(ASEAN) urged member countries to make more related efforts to
promote trade and free movement of goods in the region.
</P>
<P>
According to the ministers, ASEAN's Common Effective
Preferential Tariff (CEPT) scheme has made remarkable achievements
with intra-ASEAN exports of CEPT products rising by 21 percent to
59.3 billion US dollars in 1995 from 49.1 billion US dollars in
1994.
</P>
<P>
They said they expected the tariff range of CEPT products to be
reduced to between zero and five percent by the year 2000, thus
enabling ASEAN to establish AFTA ahead of the scheduled time of
2003.
</P>
<P>
They agreed to recommend to leaders of the ASEAM countries that
additional measures be considered to facilitate goods in transit.
</P>
<P>
The ministers praised the establishment of trade and investment
linkages between AFTA and the Australia-New Zealand Closer
Economic Relations Trade Agreement and called for similar linkages
with other regional groupings and trading arrangements.  
</P>
</TEXT>
