<DATE_TIME> 1996-07-21 08:15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Israeli Army Freezes Action of Easing Closure on </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, July 21 (Xinhua) -- Israeli Army today decided to
freeze the action of easing the closure on Palestinian
territories, in an effort to force the Palestinian police to
release an abducted Israeli citizen.
</P>
<P>
According to the measures announced by Israeli Army last week,
the easing of the closure was to go into effect today aimed at
allowing over 10,000 Palestinian workers to enter Israel to work
and increasing the inflow of the Palestinian goods.
</P>
<P>
The closure was imposed late February after the Islamic
militants launched the first of four suicide bombing attacks,
which killed 58 people and wounded nearly two hundred others
inside Israel.
</P>
<P>
However, Israel backed off from the decision after reports
said an Israeli Arab citizen living in the Old City of
Jerusalem was abducted by Palestinian security forces over a
dispute over the ownership of a shop.
</P>
<P>
The 50-year-old Arab resident, named Abed Salam Harbawi, was
taken Saturday by half a dozen of Palestinian agents who broke
into his home and fired twice into the floor before leading him
away by force.
</P>
<P>
The family of Harbawi claimed the incident arose from a
dispute over legal rights to their leather goods shop in the Old
City. The Harbawis, who are Moslem, alleged that Christian Copts,
aided by Palestinian National Authority (PNA) President Yasser
Arafat, were trying to seize from them control of a large
warehouse under their factory.
</P>
<P>
On Saturday night, Israeli forces imposed a blockade of the
PNA controlled Ramallah area to pressure the Palestinian
security forces to release Harbawi as soon as possible.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the Prime Minister's Office also issued a tough
statement demanding the immediate release of Harbawi. The
statement called the incident as a "serious matter".
</P>
<P>
By Saturday night, Palestinian security chief Jibri Rajoub
refused to free Harbawi, on grounds that he only took orders from
Arafat.
</P>
<P>
Israeli military sources said the two sides were to meet
today to discuss the matter as well as a number of similar
violations by Palestinian security services and police.
</P>
<P>
The incident is expected to deepen the Israeli-Palestinian
dispute over the status of Jerusalem.
</P>
<P>
Israel's new government led by the hardline Likud party has
declared Jerusalem as Israel's eternal and indivisible capital,
threatening to shut all PNA institutions in east Jerusalem,
especially the activities by Palestinian police.
</P>
<P>
Under the Oslo peace accords, the status of Jerusalem
should be determined in the final status talks, which opened
in May but were delayed indefinitely due to the May 29
Israeli elections.
</P>
<P>
Israeli new Prime Minister Benjamin Netanyahu has promised to
continue the final status talks, although refusing to fix any
date.
</P>
<P>
Moreover, it remains doubtful if the talks will achieve any
progress as Israel has ruled out any compromise on the issue of
Jerusalem. The PNA insists that east Jerusalem be the capital of a
future independent Palestinian state, which is also strongly
denied by the Israeli new government. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
