<DATE_TIME> 1996-07-21 08:18 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Saudi Arabia Awards Power Project to Japanese </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUWAIT CITY, July 21 (Xinhua) -- Saudi Arabia awarded Saturday
the building of a 1.108 billion U.S. dollars power plant to
Japan's Mitsubishi Heavy Industries following months of talks with
international firms, Kuwaiti newspapers reported today.
</P>
<P>
The papers, citing a press release by the state-run Saudi
Consolidated Electric Company-East (Sceco-East), said that it
awarded the bidding to Mitsubishi to build and install the power
plant at a price of 4,155 million Riyals (1.108 billion
U.S. dollars).
</P>
<P>
It said work on the project would start immediately.
</P>
<P>
The project is part of a basket plan to raise power generation
in the oil-rich kingdom to 60,000 megawatts over 25 years from a
current 17,700 megawatt capacity which is expected to be at a cost
of 117 billion dollars.
</P>
<P>
Industry experts in the kingdom said Saudi Arabia is in urgent
need of increasing power capacity to help promote industrial
development.
</P>
<P>
Mitsubishi was selected from several international bidders
including General Electric, Asea Brown Boveri and Westinghouse
Electric Corp and its selection was "based on objective and
professional analysis," the release said.
</P>
<P>
Sceco-East said it expected the first unit of the plant to be
operational in December 1999, while the second in February 2,000,
the Third and fourth in 2001 and 2002 respectively.
</P>
<P>
But the local reports did not give details on the generation
capacity of the units when their installation is completed.
</P>
<P>
Saudi Arabia is the biggest oil producer and exporter in
the world. It is expanding its power capabilities to cope
with a rapid increase in demand due to population and
industrial growth. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
