<HEADLINE> Afghan Alliance to Set up Council for Power Transfer </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ISLAMABAD, July 21 (Xinhua) -- The new Broad-Based Islamic
National Front for Peace in Afghanistan has announced its decision
to establish a "responsible and acceptable Shura" (working
council) for power transfer from President Burhanuddin Rabbani, a
local press report said today.
</P>
<P>
Signatories of this six-party alliance, including head of the
National Islamic Front of Afghanistan Ahmad Gilani and northern
warlord General Rashid Dostum, have stressed that the front is
formed not merely in opposition to Rabbani in Kabul nor is it in
support of the Taliban student militia.
</P>
<P>
They said the alliance, open to all Afghan parties, factions,
and individuals irrespective of nationality, language or sect,
aims to create the basis for the transfer of power to an
acceptable elected body, encourage national unity and ensure the
reconstruction of Afghanistan.
</P>
<P>
They called upon all parties, groups, and individuals in the
country to join the alliance for national cooperation, unity and
understanding.
</P>
<P>
A joint statement issued Saturday said that the new alliance
has agreed to adopt a joint defense policy in case of any
political or military intimidation.
</P>
<P>
It also decided to hold regular meetings of the working
council, comprising three representatives from each of the six
member parties, in the second largest Afghan city of Jalalabad or
in any other province if needed.  
</P>
</TEXT>
