<DATE_TIME> 1996-07-21 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Energy Consumption Down In Shanghai </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SHANGHAI, July 21 (Xinhua) -- The adjustment of the industrial
structure along with the rapid development of the tertiary, and
new and hi-tech industries has dramatically reduced unit energy
consumption in China's leading industrial city.
</P>
<P>
Statistics show that the energy consumption for each 100
million yuan of GDP dropped by 59 percent from 1990 to 1995, and
rolled steel, copper and timber consumption for each 100 million
yuan of industrial output value fell by 52 percent, 64 percent and
57 percent, respectively.
</P>
<P>
The fast increasing value in the city's tertiary industry has
soared to 40.7 percent of GDP, a record high, and the proportion
of new and hi-tech industry has climbed from two percent to 10.6
percent in the city's gross industrial output value.
</P>
<P>
As a result, Shanghai had saved 27.12 million tons of standard
coal, 2.59 million tons of steel and 2.25 million cubic meters of
timber during the past Five Years.
</P>
<P>
Many enterprises have made an effort to promote energy-saving
projects, which have yielded not only direct economic results, but
indirect results in social benefits and environmental protection
as well. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
