<HEADLINE> Jordan's Price Index Increases 4.24 Percent </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
AMMAN, July 21 (Xinhua) -- The prices of 726 commodities and
services have increased nearly 4.24 percent in the first half of
1996 compared with the price index at the end of last year, a
study shows.
</P>
<P>
The study, conducted by the Jordanian Consumer Protection
Society last month in three major cities -- Amman, Zarqa and
Irbid, which comprised of nearly 75 percent of the nations
population, said prices of 17 commodities rose by 4.11 percent.
</P>
<P>
These commodities included fruits, vegetables, groceries, fish,
poultry and meat, stationary, clothing and shoes as well as
electricity, water, fuel, rent and maintenance services.
</P>
<P>
The average increase in prices was calculated on average
prices recorded in the first six months of this year compared to
the rates available at the end of 1995.
</P>
<P>
The survey showed that an average Jordanian family spends 43
percent of their income on food, 25.6 percent on housing, 8.9
percent on clothing, 1.5 percent on shoes, 3.9 percent on
furniture, 5.9 percent on health services and medicines, two
percent on stationery and 4.35 on education.
</P>
<P>
It also indicated that the average prices of vegetables rose
in the first half of this year by 13.1 percent, groceries
2.4 percent, other food supplies 2.96 percent, water, telephone
and fuel 15.86 percent, fish and poultry and meat 6.04 percent.
</P>
</TEXT>
