<HEADLINE> ASEAN FMs Call for Efforts to Reduce Trade Barriers </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JAKARTA, July 21 (Xinhua) -- Foreign ministers of the
Association of Southeast Asian Nations (ASEAN) today called for
continued efforts to reduce barriers in trade and investment in
the region.
</P>
<P>
In a joint communique issued at the end of the 29th ASEAN
Ministerial Meeting (AMM) here, the ministers announced the target
of removing by this year all customs surcharges affecting products
identified under ASEAN's Common Effective Preferential Tariff
(CEPT) scheme.
</P>
<P>
The ministers urged ASEAN member countries to strengthen their
efforts to eliminate non-tariff barriers.
</P>
<P>
They praised the rapid developments made in customs cooperation
to support the ASEAN Free Trade Area (AFTA), especially the
establishment of the Green Lane system for CEPT products to
expedite their customs clearance.
</P>
<P>
The ASEAN will later come up with an agreement aimed at
enhancing regional cooperation in customs, they said.
</P>
<P>
They expressed optimism about the full implementation of trade
facilitation measures under AFTA, particularly the harmonization
of tariff nomenclature, customs procedures and customs valuation.
 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
