<DOCNO> XIE19960721.0091 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1996-07-21 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Guangdong to Boost Large State Enterprises </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, July 21 (Xinhua) -- To stimulate its state-owned
economy, Guangdong Province in south China has issued ten
favorable measures to boost the development of the major state
enterprises, reported today's China Daily.
</P>
<P>
Large state firms will have more power and freedom in finance,
import and export, annexation of smaller firms, project approval
and property rights transfer.
</P>
<P>
The measures aim to build a considerable number of giant
state-owned firms into leaders of the local economy. Each of these
firms is expected to achieve annual sales of between three billion
yuan (361 million US dollars) and 10 billion yuan (1.2 billion Us
dollars) by the year 2000.
</P>
<P>
Bearing the province's hopes of restructuring the sluggish
state economic sector, these firms will appear as trans-regional
or trans-national group enterprises that combine industry,
technology, trade and finance.
</P>
<P>
To give them more financial power, the new measures encourage
the firms to set up their own financial clearing centers or even
financial companies. They will also have the support of the
provincial government to participate in the operation of such
financial organs as urban co-operative banks and trust and
investment companies.
</P>
<P>
They will take priority in approval and arrangement of projects
from the local government. Qualified firms will be chosen as the
main body to undertake the province's key projects. They will have
the local government's support in setting up their own offices and
distribution operations. They will also enjoy favorable terms in
import permits and quotas.
</P>
<P>
Annexation of smaller firms is also encouraged in order to
hasten the growth of these group companies.
</P>
<P>
To help them pay off their debts and raise capital, the
measures allow these firms to transfer part of the property rights
of some of their subsidiaries to foreign or local businesses.
</P>
<P>
And in the three years starting from this year, the local
government will return 15 percent of the profit tax payment by
these firms as state capital investment in them.
</P>
<P>
Seventy firms have just been chosen by the provincial
government as the first group of "key state firms."
</P>
<P>
These enterprises now make up 44.6 percent of the total assets
of the province's 18,162 state firms, 41.9 and 53.5 percent
respectively of the total sale and profit of all the industrial
enterprises in the province. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
