<DOCNO> XIE19960721.0092 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1996-07-21 07:57 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Report: France Adamant On Activity In East Jerusalem </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, July 21 (Xinhua) -- French Foreign Minister Herve
de Charette will reaffirm, during his visit to Israel this week,
his country's insistence that Orient House, the PLO's office in
East Jerusalem, be allowed its activities, reported The Jerusalem
Post today.
</P>
<P>
The paper quoted a high-level French official as saying that
France also insists that free access to the building be assured.
</P>
<P>
The rightwing Likud government has hardened the country's
position regarding Orient House, threatening to close it if any
foreign officials call at the building. There had been an
understanding between the European Union and the Labor government
that EU leaders refrain from a visit to the building, but
officials at foreign minister-level are not affected. The
European countries have so far refused to acknowledge Israel's
insistence that Jerusalem is its sole and eternal capital.
</P>
<P>
The official told the paper, however, that he would not
confirm whether de Charette will visit the PLO's office.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, French Foreign Ministry spokesman said, "You shall
have to wait and see. The minister will make his decision on
the spot, we'll do what we judge to be useful."
</P>
<P>
Asked whether de Charette would try to visit Orient House
even if the Israeli government decided to surround the
building with security personnel to prevent such a visit, the
spokesman replied: "We will not give in to pressures."
</P>
<P>
Israeli diplomats in Paris said, however, that the French
government will avoid a diplomatic crisis and de Charette will
not pay a visit to the controversial establishment, limiting
himself to a meeting with (PA President Yasser) Arafat in
Gaza only.
</P>
<P>
De Charette will arrive in Damascus Monday, his first stop
in the region. On Tuesday, he will visit Lebanon, Jordan and
Gaza, ending his Middle East tour on Wednesday with visits
to Israel and Egypt.
</P>
<P>
Since the new government took office, France has asserted its
traditional influence in the Middle East. It played a big role in
helping brought about a cease-fire agreement to end Israel's
Operation Grapes of Wrath in Lebanon in April. De Charette
conducted a diplomatic shuttle between Lebanon, Syria and Israel,
which was very much appreciated by the Arabs.
</P>
<P>
This time De Charette's tour is aimed primarily at expressing
France's and Europe's belief that the peace process must
continue on the basis of the right to self-determination and
the principle of land-for- peace, according to the French
Foreign Ministry spokesman. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
