<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Israel to Transfer Soldiers' Remains to Lebanon </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Kafr Tibnit, Lebanon, July 21 (Xinhua) -- Israel is to hand
over the remains of about 150 Hezbollah guerrillas to the Lebanese
government through the International Red Cross Committee (IRCC)
today.
</P>
<P>
The hand-over will be conducted at a square in Kafr Tibnit
village on the Israeli-Lebanese border in the Israeli self-claimed
"Security Zone" in south Lebanon. At 8:00 local time (0500 GMT),
50 ambulances of the Red Cross were seen arriving at the village
and scores of the Red Cross personnel surrounded the square.
</P>
<P>
The remains of the soldiers to be handed over by Israel are
expected to be placed at the square to facilitate a check by the
Red Cross.
</P>
<P>
The remains will be transferred from Israel to the IRCC, which
will in turn hand over them to the Lebanese government. An IRCC
official said that the remains of the guerrillas will be ferried
to the village in two batches, and the first of which will arrive
here this morning.
</P>
<P>
In addition, Israel will also hand over 45 prisoners to
Lebanon. The prisoners were jailed at Khiam deeply inside the
Israeli self-proclaimed "security zone" in south Lebanon,
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the Lebanese authorities are expected to hand over
the remains of two Israeli soldiers and two militia of the South
Lebanese Army (SLA) to a German delegation at the Beirut
international airport. The German delegation is responsible for
transporting the remains of Cyprus by air.
</P>
<P>
As Hezbollah called on the families of the dead soldiers to
converge in the village today, about 3,000 of them arrived by 9:00
a.m. (0600 GMT) and many more are expected to arrive later.
</P>
<P>
According to Red Cross officials, only nine of the 150 remains
have been identified.
</P>
<P>
A middle-aged man told Xinhua that four of his sons died of the
military operations against Israel in south Lebanon in 1987.
</P>
<P>
Bernd Schmidbauer, German minister of state for security
affairs, is expected to fly to the Beirut airport today from
Damascus to pick up the remains and SLA prisoners.
</P>
<P>
At the end of the repatriation, the German official, who is
also a top intelligence adviser to Chancellor Helmut Kohl, will
hold a press conference to talk on details of the operation,
reliable official sources said on condition of anonymity.
</P>
<P>
Schmidbauer was sent by his government to broker the deal
among Lebanon, Israel and Syria.
</P>
<P>
Philipe Gayar, IRCC's top representative in Lebanon, announced
in Beirut Saturday that the parties concerned in Lebanon, Israel
and Germany had contacted the international organization to seek
help in carrying out the operation, including providing vehicles.
</P>
<P>
After meeting the German mediator in Damascus, Hezbollah's
Secretary General Sheikh Hassan Nasrallah announced that his
party had endorsed the swap deal which is to be executed today.
</P>
<P>
He described the German-brokered agreement as "an advancing
step on the road to a solution of the problem facing all the
prisoners held by Israel, the most prominent of whom are Sheikh
Abdel Karim Abeid and Mostafa Dirani."
</P>
<P>
Abeid and Dirani were abducted from their homes by Israeli
commandos in 1989 and 1994 respectively.
</P>
<P>
Israel said that the two Hezbollah leaders would not be
released until it finds out what had happened to four other
Israeli military servicemen missing in southern Lebanon since
1986, including air force pilot Ron Arad. Israel believes Arad is
still alive.
</P>
<P>
Lebanon's government insists that the operation of swap be
conducted under its supervision.
</P>
<P>
"The exchange will be completed with the government's
knowledge and under its supervision and by the goodwill efforts
of the German government which sent Minister Schmidbauer to
contact with all the parties," said Interior Minister Michel
Al-Murr Friday. 
</P>
</TEXT>
