<DATE_TIME> 1996-07-21 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Zambia's Copper Co. to Be Privatized in Stages </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUSAKA, July 21 (Xinhua) -- The Zambia Consolidated Copper
Mines (ZCCM), the government-monopolized conglomerate in the
copper industry, will be privatized in two stages by mid-1998.
</P>
<P>
This was announced in a statement released by a ZCCM spokesman
in Ndola of Copperbelt Province on Saturday.
</P>
<P>
The ZCCM board has approved and adopted recommendations for
the two-stage privatization plan of the company.
</P>
<P>
In the first stage of the program which is expected to
complete by June next year, substantial majority interest in all
of the ZCCM's major operating and development assets will be
offered in separate packages to mining companies and other trade
investors.
</P>
<P>
This will leave the ZCCM as the owner of the minority
interests in operations managed by in-coming investors.
</P>
<P>
In the second stage, the government intends to dispose all, or
substantial part of its shareholding in the ZCCM with the shares
being distributed widely to the Zambian people and other
financial institutions in and outside the country.
</P>
<P>
ZCCM Board Chairman Luke Mwananshiku was quoted today by the
local press as saying that the board is united in wanting the
company's operations to move into private control and ownership
quickly and effectively.
</P>
<P>
The ZCCM earns the country 80 percent of its foreign exchanges
yearly. However, it has faced liquidity problems in recent years
because of the low copper output resulted from the obsolete
equipment the company used in mining.
</P>
<P>
The company has said it has no financial ability for
improvement by itself.
</P>
<P>
To improve its management and production, the Zambian
government has been for some time formulating a policy such as
privatization along with economic reforms to promote copper
production in the country. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
