<HEADLINE> Uganda Ranks Second in Africa's Road Traffic </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KAMPALA, July 21 (Xinhua) -- Uganda ranks second after
Ethiopia in road traffic accidents in Africa, reported "the New
Vision" paper today.
</P>
<P>
Chief traffic officer in Kampala, capital of Uganda Grace
Turyagumanawe was quoted as saying that according to 1995
statistics, Uganda has 161 fatalities per 10,000 motor vehicles
followed by Ghana with 111 accidents while Ethiopia ranks first
with 215 fatal accidents per 10,000 vehicles.
</P>
<P>
Addressing a closing ceremony of a one-week in-country road
safety workshop on Saturday, the officer disclosed that the
situation might worsen due to a likely increase in registration
to 20,000 new vehicles this year.
</P>
<P>
The traffic carnage has been rising year after year, he
asserted.
</P>
<P>
He said most of the victims are innocent pedestrians,
particularly children below 20.
</P>
<P>
Turyagumanawe however lashed out at "incompetent and reckless
drivers who have no regard for passengers' safety", and also
lamented the poor design of roads in the country.
</P>
<P>
He finally urged parliament to pass the traffic and road
safety bill as soon as possible since 1970 traffic act has
outlived its usefulness. 
</P>
</TEXT>
