<HEADLINE> Claudia Poll Takes Olympics Naturally </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ATLANTA, July 20 (Xinhua) -- "I will try to stay cool and take
it (the Olympic competition) naturally," said Claudia Poll of
Costa Rica, who is probably South America's only hope of an
Olympic swimming medal at the Atlanta Games here.
</P>
<P>
"I want to have fun there (at Olympics). It'll be just another
swimming competition -- the most important one of the year," she
said.
</P>
<P>
"It sounds weird, but for me Atlanta is already over. We have
so many plans for the coming years. The Olympics are important
but not ther only thing," she claimed.
</P>
<P>
However, more striking than her somewhat nonchalant attitude
towards the 1996 Centennial Olympic Games is Poll's extremely
disciplined approach to the sport.
</P>
<P>
"I came here to compete," she said. "Im very meticulous with
what I do. I have fun doing it but I do it with discipline."
</P>
<P>
Although a first-time Olympian, Poll is already a seasoned
international performer. Career highlights include a bronze medal
in the 200 meters freestyle at the 1994 world championships, where
she clocked one minute 57.61, and more recently two gold medals at
the 1995 short-course world championships in Rio de Janeiro. In
winning the 200 meters freestyle event, she also established a
world record.
</P>
<P>
Poll's versatility is evident in the fact that she holds
virtually every national freestyle record, in addition to her
sport course world mark in the 200 meters freestyle. Though she
obviously would be pleased with a medal performance in Atlanta,
Poll's main goal is to imporve her times in the middle distance
freestyle events.
</P>
<P>
"I want to do better times, but my happiness doesn't depend on
winning a medal," Poll said. "I always swim my race. A world
record might change people's image of you, but the world record
doesn't swim the race for you," she said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
