<HEADLINE> Sievinen, Palmer in Olympic Swim-off Oddity </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ATLANTA, July 20 (Xinhua) -- Jani Sievinen of Finland and Paul
Palmer of Britain said the swim-off they took in one of the
Olympic swimming's heats here today shocked them and it was
something they had never experienced.
</P>
<P>
In the preliminaries of men's 200 meters freestyle this
morning, they two clocked an identical times of one minute 49.05
seconds, which placed them eighth overall.
</P>
<P>
As only eight swimmers are allowed to qualified for the finals,
the tie warranted a swim-off between them to decide who would
advance to this evening's final.
</P>
<P>
In the swim-off shortly after, the two swimmers raced
head-to-head and again matched each other's performance at
1:48.85. Both the athletes were given the option of a third race.
</P>
<P>
But Sievinen declined due to his busy schedule while Palmer
thus advanced to the final.  The Finish will have 100 and 200
meters backstrokes, 200 and 400 meters individual medleys and the
4x100 meters freestyle relay.
</P>
<P>
Palmer also is tightly scheduled, with races in 400 and 800
meters freestyle and 4x200 meters freestyle relay.
</P>
<P>
Both of them competed in the Barcelona Olympic Games and have
never swum a swim-off.
</P>
<P>
"If I have to, I'll swim again," said Palmer, before learning
that Sievinen deffered the eighth position. "I havee never, ever
had a swim-off! You can't print what I thoughtt when I saw it," he
said.
</P>
<P>
"I have never had a swim off in my life! I can't believe it,"
Sivinen said. "When I turned around and saw the board I though to
myself, "Oh no!'" 
</P>
</TEXT>
