NEW DELHI, July 21 (Xinhua) -- The union budget for 1996-97 to
be presented to parliament on July 22 is expected to cut fiscal
deficit and give more attention to social agenda, economists said
here today.
</P>
<P>
It will also encourage more savings and foreign direct
investment in the country.
</P>
<P>
The fiscal challenge has been underlined in the updated
economic survey for 1995-96 tabled in the parliament by the
finance minister on last Friday. Given the target of the common
minimum program of the united front government announced on June 5
to contain fiscal deficit at 4 percent of the GDP, Finance
Minister P. Chidambaram is likely to adopt such a strategy in his
maiden budget which would move towards that objective. Reduction
in fiscal deficit would mean lower borrowings so that private
investments are not crowded out and deficit liabilities are not
further built up, the economists said.
</P>
<P>
Chidambaram is expected to enforce certain discipline through
greater expenditure control. He is helpless insofar as the
mounting subsidies and other inescapable expenditure, including
interest and defense, are concerned, they said.
</P>
<P>
The government is also expected to focus its attention on
alleviation of poverty and thus give more outlay for social agenda
such as improving drinking water, health and education for the
poor as they promised in the election campaign, they added.
</P>
</TEXT>
