<DOCNO> XIE19960721.0118 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1996-07-21 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Roundup: Mindanao Peace Deal Provokes Stormy Debate </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, July 21 (Xinhua) -- A month after the Philippine
government and a Muslim rebel group forged an agreement on peace
in Mindanao, no one now seems to know when the stormy debate on
the peace deal could end and when the peace deal would be
finalized.
</P>
<P>
At the June 21-23 talks in Davao city, the southern
Philippines, government negotiators and representatives of the
Moro National Liberation Front (MNLF) reached the agreement to end
a 24-year old war in Mindanao, which claimed over 50,000 lives.
</P>
<P>
Under the peace agreement, President Fidel Ramos will create a
MNLF-led Southern Philippines Council for Peace and Development
that will lead to a new, broader autonomous region covering 14
provinces and 10 cities in the south.
</P>
<P>
A referendum will be held in three years to determine which of
the 14 provinces and 10 cities will join the new autonomous
region, which will replace the current autonomous region that
includes only four Muslim-dominated provinces.
</P>
<P>
Political analysts believe that the agreement offers best hope
for peace in Mindanao, an traditional homeland of the country's
five million Muslim minority.
</P>
<P>
However, ever since the peace deal came to light, it has
provoked an endless and heated debate between the government
peacemakers and those who saw it not a formula for peace but of
appeasement.
</P>
<P>
some congressmen claimed that they were not at all consulted
before the deal was forged and therefore the creation of the
MNLF-led council was unconstitutional.
</P>
<P>
Critics, mostly from the majority Christian population in
Mindanao, said that the government is effectively imposing Muslim
rule on Christian regions without any consultations with the
affected communities.
</P>
<P>
Other opponents accused the government of favoring only MNLF
Chairman Nur Misuari, who has been promised the chairmanship of
the council and will run for governor of the current autonomous
region in Mindanao in September as a candidate of Ramos' political
party--Lakas National Union of Christian Democrats (NUCD).
</P>
<P>
The opponents also charged that the proposed new autonomous
region covered more than the one stipulated in the 1976 Tripoli
agreement, under which the MNLF abandoned its goal of complete
independence and instead accepted the idea of autonomy in
Mindanao.
</P>
<P>
In the face of the strong opposition, President Ramos and other
government officials appealed to the nation to give peace a chance
in Mindanao and consistently defended the peace deal as the best
formula for peace in the southern Philippines.
</P>
<P>
During the past month, Ramos used all kinds of tactics to win
the opponents to the government side. He traveled to the south to
seek support for the agreement. He invited the governors and
mayors and representatives from the affected areas, including the
critics, to a dinner in the presidential palace to win their
confidence in the deal. He ordered the government negotiators to
reveal the major points of the agreements reached with the MNLF in
the past three years, in an attempt to ease suspicions of a secret
deal with the rebel group.
</P>
<P>
With the painstaking efforts by the government, some opponents
agreed to "give peace a chance in Mindanao," while maintaining
their positions. But others are still challenging the legality of
the proposed council.
</P>
<P>
As the stormy debate is continuing nationwide, the negotiations
between the government and the MNLF are going on and in fact still
deadlocked on two contentious issues-- the integration of the MNLF
into the government army and the national police, and the creation
of a special regional security force in Mindanao.
</P>
<P>
The government army is prepared to take in 5,500 MNLF fighters
while the national police will take in 1,000, but the rebel group
insists that at least 7,500 fighters be integrated into the
government army and the police.
</P>
<P>
the MNLF also demand the formation of a 20,000 special regional
security force to be placed under Misuari's direct control and
command. however, the demand has been flatly rejected by the
government.
</P>
<P>
after the June 21-23 peace talks, the government and the MNLF
planned to start their final round of negotiations in Jakarta on
July 10-15. but now even president Ramos could not tell when the
negotiation can be wrapped up.
</P>
<P>
he said earlier this week that there is "a wish" that the final
peace accord will be ready for signing in Jakarta a month or two
from now.
</P>
<P>
so unsure is the outcome of the on-going peace talks that
neither side could guess when a final peace accord could be
forged. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
