<HEADLINE> Nepali Opposition Against Treaty with India </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KATHMANDU, July 21 (Xinhua) -- The Communist Party of Nepal
(CPN-UML), the country's main opposition, will not support a
border river treaty with India in the ongoing parliament session,
UML-UML President Man Mohan Adhikari said Saturday.
</P>
<P>
This was the first time that the CPN-UML publicly voiced its
objection to the Mahakali Treaty signed by Nepali Prime Minister
Sher Bahadur Deuba and the then Indian Prime Minister P.V.
Narasimha Rao in February.
</P>
<P>
The treaty, hailed earlier as a landmark in the bilateral
cooperation on water resources development, provides that Nepal
has rights over any future water projects on the border river on
an equitable basis.
</P>
<P>
The Nepali government Friday registered the treaty in the
parliament secretariat for ratification.
</P>
<P>
"We want to further study all the aspects of the treaty, but
the government is in a hurry to ratify it," said Adhikari, whose
party holds 89 seats in the 205-seat lower house.
</P>
<P>
The support of the CPN-UML is considered to be crucial to the
ratification of the treaty, which requires a two-third majority in
the house.  
</P>
</TEXT>
