<HEADLINE> Le Wins First Olympic Swimming Title at Atlanta Games </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ATLANTA, July 20 (Xinhua) -- China's world champion Le Jingyi
again showed her stable superiority by winning the first gold
medal of the swimming competitions at the 26th Summer Olympic
Games here on Saturday.
</P>
<P>
Le, 21, world record holder and top qualifier this morning,
clocked a winning time of 54.50 for her first Olympic title.
</P>
<P>
"I was pleased, because for an athlete, the Olympic Games' gold
are the top honor. Today is the most important day in my life."
Le was quite excited at the press conference.
</P>
<P>
The veteran of the Chinese squad, who is making her second
Olympic appearance after Barcelona, was behind American Angel
Matino, but was ahead of another American Amy van Dyken, at the 50
meters turn.
</P>
<P>
But Le found the steam in the latter half of the course and
beat Germany's Sandra Volker and Martino into the second and third
places, at 54.88 and 54.93 respectively.
</P>
<P>
Martino, pumped up by the partisan home fans, was satisfied
with the medal, the first medal ever for the hosts at the
Centennial Olympic Games.
</P>
<P>
Le's coach Zhou Ming said that he was satisfied with the
results Le scored.
</P>
<P>
"Le had already got Olympic experiences, that's why she could
win the gold this evening."
</P>
<P>
Zhou explained other Chinese swimmers' disappointing
performances in the morning's hear were due to lacking of
experiences.
</P>
<P>
"They didn't have much international experiences and seemed
just too nervous," Zhou said.
</P>
<P>
He said that Chinese coaches would try to solve the problem.
</P>
<P>
"We hope we can solve the problem and do well in the coming
days."
</P>
<P>
Chen Yan and Wu Yanyan, Chinese hopefuls in the women's
400-meter individual medley, failed to make the final.
</P>
<P>
"We had mixed feeling in the pool today," Zhou said, "Le
performed well while Zeng Qiliang had gained the first final berth
for the Chinese male swimmers, while some of the young swimmers
didn't perform well."
</P>
<P>
Zeng finished seventh with 1:02.01 in the men's 100m
breaststroke, which was won by the Belgium's Fred Deburghgraeve,
who had set a new world mark in this morning's heat.
</P>
<P>
The Belgian clocked 1:00.65, just 0.05 seconds out of his fresh
new record.
</P>
<P>
Michelle Smith from Ireland chalked up the women's 400m
individual medley at 4:39.18.
</P>
<P>
Smith, runner-up at the 1995 European Championships, said that
she just tried her best.
</P>
<P>
The second-time Olympian said that her parents taught her
swimming just for safety reason.
</P>
<P>
Asked about the key for her victory, she said that was "hard
work and the smart training".
</P>
<P>
New Zealand's Danyon Loader grabbed the men's 200m freestyle
title with a time of 1:47.63, edging Brazilian veteran Gustavo
Borges into the second, at 1:48.08. 
</P>
</TEXT>
