<DOCNO> XIE19960721.0129 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1996-07-21 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> First-day Olympic Golds Spread Among Teams </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ATLANTA, July 20 (Xinhua) -- The first ten gold medals at stake
in the first day of the 26th Olympic Games here were shared among
nine participating teams with China enjoying an early lead with
two gold and two silver medals.
</P>
<P>
Belgium, France, Ireland, Italy, New Zealand, Poland, Russia
and Turkey collected one gold medal each in the day's competition
which provided quite a few impressive scenes.
</P>
<P>
Host the United States, generally seen as the biggest sporting
power, ended the day without a single gold. Its swimmers met with
strong challenges in the swimming pool and had to be contended
with two silver and one bronze medals.
</P>
<P>
Two world record breaking performances in the swimming and
weightlifting events lifted the morale of the organizers and
participants alike.
</P>
<P>
Little known Fred Deburghgraeve from Belgium broke the world
record in the men's 100m breaststoke by clocking 1:00.60 in the
morning heats. Later in the final race, he returned five hundredth
of a second outside his new world mark to bag the gold medal.
</P>
<P>
Turkey's Halil Mutlu snatched 132.5 kilograms to better his own
world mark of 130.5kg set in May of 1995 on his way to defeat
China's world champion Zhang Xiangsen for the gold in the 54kg
category of the weightlifting competition with a two-lift total of
287.5kg. Zhang took the silver with 280kg and Sedvalin Minchev of
Bulgaria got the bronze with 277.5kg.
</P>
<P>
China's world record holder Le Jingyi showed her
prowess by beating Germany's Sandra Volker and American Angel
Martino in the women's 100m freestyle final with a time of 54.50
seconds.
</P>
<P>
Earlier, Sun Fuming won China's first gold in this Olympics by
overwhelmning several world-famous opponents in the over-72kg
category of the women's judo competition.
</P>
<P>
In a dramatic scene at the Wolf Creek Shooting Complex, world
champion Wang Yifu of China suffered a blackout in the last shot of the
men's 10m air pistol final and was overtaken by Italian Roberto Di
Donna by the margin of one-tenth of a point.
</P>
<P>
Poland's Renata Mauer won this Olympics' first gold medal in
the women's 10m air rifle event against a strong field including
Germany's Petra Horneber and world champion Vessela Jetchevea of
Bulgaria.
</P>
<P>
In the men's epee final, Russian Aleksandr Beketov outfenced
Ivan Trevejo Perez of Cuba 15-14 to claim the first fencing title
of the present Olympic Games.
</P>
<P>
France netted a gold through David Douillet in the men's over
95kg judo tournament who won from Spain's Ernesto Perez in the
final bout this afternoon.
</P>
<P>
Michelle Smith of Ireland displayed an impressive burst of
force in the last leg of the women's 400m individual medley final,
beating American Allison Wagner and Hungary's Krisztina Egerszegi
by almost three full seconds.
</P>
<P>
New Zealander Danyon Loader swam to a gold medal in the men's
200m freestyle.
</P>
<P>
Three to six matches were played each in the soccer, hockey,
basketball, volleyball, baseball and water polo competitions.
</P>
<P>
Chinese men's baskball team overcame African champion Angola
70-67 in a preliminary encounter while its women's volleyball
squad won from European champion the Nethlands 15-10, 15-5,
10-7.
</P>
<P>
Spain pulled off a surprise 1-0 win from the defending champion
Germany in the men's hockey preliminaries while Argentina
defeated Pakistan 1-0 in another group match.
</P>
<P>
