<HEADLINE> Russia Takes Lead after Men's Team Compulsories </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ATLANTA, June 20 (Xinhua) -- Alexei Nemov socred the day's
highest total of 57.862 points to lead a well-balanced Russian
team on top of the standings after the men's team compulsory
competitions here on Satursday.
</P>
<P>
The Russian squad collected a total of 287.258 points to beat
1995 world champions China into the second place in 286.283.
</P>
<P>
Ukraine came into the third place with 285.359.
</P>
<P>
Li Xiaoshuang of China was the day's biggest disappointment
when the world all-around champion was forced to stop amid his
performance on the rings and got just 8.350 points.
</P>
<P>
The Russian team are the arch-rivals to the world championships
winners China at the Centennial Olympic Games at Atlanta.
</P>
<P>
"By trailing almost one point (0.975), it'll be very hard to
catch up with the Russians in the optional rotations," said
Chinese head coach Gao Jian.
</P>
<P>
China, started on the vaulting horse, led Russian through five
rotations before Li make his mistake on the rings.
</P>
<P>
"I didn't expect it at all," said Li Xiaoshuang, "The rings is
one of my best events and I've never make that kind of mistakes
before."
</P>
<P>
Li Xiaoshuang is now ranking at the 29th among the 112 gymnasts
participating in Saturday's competitions and only the top 36
finishers after both the compulosaries and optionals could enter
the finals of the individual all-around.
</P>
<P>
Six-time Olympic gold medalist Vitaly Scherbo chalked up 57.823
points to give Belarus a fourth spot among the top eight teams.
</P>
<P>
The men's team optionals competitions are scheduled on Monday
while the Women's team compulsories will be held on Sunday.
</P>
