<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China Wins Volleyball Opener at Atlanta Olympics </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ATLANTA, July 20 (Xinhua) -- World Cup bronze medalists China
won the opener of the women's volleyball tournament with three
straight sets here Saturday morning at the Atlanta Olympic Games.
</P>
<P>
The Chinese women spikers outwitted their Dutch peers, European
champions, 15-10, 15-5 and 15-7 in one hour and 13 minutes at the
Omni Coliseum.
</P>
<P>
Bidding for a spot at the ceremony podium in the Centennial
Olympics, the Chinese team was under the helm of former ace spiker
Lang Ping who orchestrated for China to win five world titles in a
row from 1981-1986.
</P>
<P>
With fierce spikes and tight blocks, the Chinese players
enjoyed visible edges at the court by winning the first two sets
with ease.
</P>
<P>
Although the Dutch women pulled up a little bit from a 0-2
deficit, the Chinese spared no efforts by winding up the
competition in another half a hour.
</P>
<P>
Lang Ping, head coach of the Chinese squad since early last
year, expressed her satisfaction with the performance of her
disciples who keep a clean 4-0 slate against the Netherlands.
</P>
<P>
In other Group A matches, South Korea also tasted the victory
by beating neighboring Japan 15-10, 15-12 and 15-10 in one hour
and 37 minutes.
</P>
<P>
However it was M. Obayashi of Japan who scored the most of
five points in their head-on-head encounter.
</P>
<P>
Host the United States won gusts of applauses from the home
audience for their win of 15-8, 15-5 and 15-11 against Ukraine
that competes for the first time in the Olympic Games.
</P>
<P>
In Group B, I. Ilchenko paced her Russian teammates to breeze
across Germany 15-5, 15-10 and 15-7 in one hour and seven minutes.
</P>
<P>
Ilchenko scored the most of 13 points throughout the
competition.
</P>
<P>
Hot favorite Cuba, reigning world and Olympic champions, reapt
an easy win over Canada 15-8, 15-8 and 15-5 in merely one hour and
four minutes even without the field-in of ace spiker Mireya Luis.
</P>
<P>
In late night, Brazil, runners-up in the World Cup, defeated
Peru 15-7, 15-1, 15-5. 
</P>
</TEXT>
