<DATE_TIME> 1996-07-21 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Banks to Better Security Measures </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, July 21 (Xinhua) -- Chinese Banks began to seek more
effective security measures from abroad, as the number of armed
robberies surged these years, according to today's China Daily.
</P>
<P>
A soldier raises a 54-style pistol and shoots at a clear
material inlaid on a metal stand some 10 meters away: it's clear
to all present that the three bullets were absorbed in the
material with nary a shard or spark in sight.
</P>
<P>
The scene was a demonstration of a bulletproof glazing material
produced by General Electric (GE) of the United States. Organized
by GE's structured products department and the Beijing
Clear-shield New Material Technology Development Center, the show
attracted dozens of officials from China's major banks and public
security authorities as well as leaders of some museums in Beijing.
</P>
<P>
A 79-style light submachine gun and a high-powered 81-style
semiautomatic rifle were also pointed at the material -- yielding
similar results.
</P>
<P>
The show comes just as China's banks and financial institutions
are strengthening security in response to a series of armed
robberies in some cities in recent years.
</P>
<P>
Cash is still the primary means of payment in China and large
amounts of it are circulated between workplaces, financial
institutions and individuals, making banks and financial
institutions favorite targets for criminals.
</P>
<P>
Last December, several armed robbers struck an armored car in
South china's Guangdong Province, the biggest bank robbery since
the founding of the People Republic of china in 1949. A chain of
bank robberies and jewellery-shop hold-ups also hit Beijing this
year, the Legal Daily reported.
</P>
<P>
Vice-Premier Zhu Rongji pointed out at a conference late last
month that the crackdown on financial crimes is a long-term task,
though major incidences of financial swindle, robbery and theft
have decreased year-on-year since 1993.
</P>
<P>
The vice-premier stressed that financial institutions should
strengthen administration and training of security personnel, as
well as boost electronic monitoring and alarm systems.
</P>
<P>
As a result, security facilities -- especially electronic
monitoring systems and armored cars and banks lobbies, have become
one of the banks' most urgent tasks.
</P>
<P>
Sources with GE said the Industrial and Commercial Bank of
China and the China Construction Bank have become the first users
of GE's bulletproof glazing materials. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19960721.0138 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1996-07-21 </DATE_TIME>
