<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Chinese Airline To Purchase 11 MD90 Planes </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, July 21 (Xinhua) -- China Aviation Supplies
Corp.(CASC), China Northern Airlines (CNA) have signed a contract
with McDonnell-Douglas of the United States to purchase eleven
MD90 passenger planes.
</P>
<P>
The contract, signed on July 17, makes CNA the first Chinese
carrier to use the new McDonnell-Douglas jetliner.
</P>
<P>
From 1996 to 1998, each year will see the delivery of three
planes, and the last two will be brought to China in 1999. The
first of the eleven will be handed over to CNA at Long Beach of
California, where McDonnell-Douglas is based, and land in CNA's
base in the northeast China city of Shenyang on August 1.
</P>
<P>
MD90-30 jetliners, the newest type in McDonnell-Douglas's
150-seaters, are an improved model from the MD80 family. China and
the US aircraft manufacturer have co-produced 35 MD80 and MD82
passenger planes since 1985, and the two signed a contract last
year to co-produce 20 MD90-30 planes in a period of five years.
</P>
<P>
Earlier this month, CASC, Air China signed a contract with
Boeing to purchase three Boeing747s, which will be delivered in
1997 and 1998.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
