<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Colombian Drug Traffickers Threaten President Samper </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SANTAFE DE BOGOTA, July 20 (Xinhua) -- A group of
"extraditable" drug traffickers on Friday issued a series of
threatening communiques after the Colombian government renew
discussions about their extradition.
</P>
<P>
National Police Director Rosso Jose Serrano Cadena said that
the communiques have been specially directed at President Ernesto
Samper and other high-ranking government officials.
</P>
<P>
"It seems logical that after the proposals made by the
president to make the penalties more severe and reopen the debate
about the extradition, those threatening communiques would be
presented," Serrano Cadena said.
</P>
<P>
One of the communiques sent to the media began, "Today, the
20th of July, the date when we celebrate the independence of our
country, we reappear to demand the refusal to extradition."
</P>
<P>
The message seemed to purport that drug traffickers do not want
to be "the scapegoat" in the Samper administration's intention to
surmount its confrontation with the U.S. government and avoid
possible economic sanctions,
</P>
<P>
"We do not want to be the only victims of the present crisis of
our nation. We will not either spoil what we won in the
Constitution of 1991. By no means will we permit being tried by
the U.S. government," added the communique.
</P>
<P>
The Colombian police intelligence department has already been
ordered by the government to study the authenticity of the
communiques and get ready to react to any disturbance of the
public order.
</P>
<P>
The United States has recently criticized Colombia for falling
short of its goals in the war against drug trafficking, implying
impending U.S. economic sanctions against Colombia. 
</P>
</TEXT>
