<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Costa Rica Takes Steps to Prevent Spread of Cholera </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SAN JOSE, July 20 (Xinhua) -- Costa Rican authorities have
ordered a more stringent border control after registering cases of
cholera in the recent days, which caused a death, in a town on the
border with Nicaragua.
</P>
<P>
Costa Rican health officials expressed concern about the rapid
spread of the illness caused by massive and uncontrolled
immigration of undocumented Nicaraguans.
</P>
<P>
One of the seven persons affected by cholera, a woman called
Antonia Aleman, died Friday in San Isidro de Pocosol, 10
kilometers from the border with Nicaragua. The six children of
the deceased woman and 18 other people have shown cholera symptoms.
</P>
<P>
The Costa Rican government has decided to create a commission
with personnel from the ministries of Health and Public Security,
the organization of judicial investigations, and the Immigration
secretariat to detect undocumented Nicaraguans.
</P>
<P>
Police and Immigration officials have effected a dragnet
operation in the border with Nicaragua to detain and deport
illegal Nicaraguans. 
</P>
</TEXT>
