<HEADLINE> Hungary Reports Sharp Rise in Crime Rates </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BUDAPEST, July 20 (Xinhua) -- The number of criminal offenses,
especially those related to money, rose sharply in Hungary in the
first half of this year, according to the Hungarian National
Police General Office today.
</P>
<P>
The number of crimes increased by 1.5 percent in the six months
over the same period of 1995, involving a total of 135 murders and
the explosion of six grenades and four home-made bombs.
</P>
<P>
In operations to fight criminal gangs, police had to open fire
on 49 occasions, the office said.
</P>
<P>
It also reported that the number of economic crimes also
reached a worrying high level, causing an estimated total loss of
850 billion forints (about 5.7 billion U.S. dollars).
</P>
<P>
In addition, the number of cases involving drug trafficking,
prostitution and car-thefts also reached "unexpected high levels,"
according to the office. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
