<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Debutant Judoka Wins China's First Olympic Gold </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ATLANTA, July 20 (Xinhua) -- To make her debut in the Olympics,
Sun Fuming became the heroine to award China its first Olympic
gold medal by winning the over 72-kg heavyweight class judo title
here Saturday afternoon.
</P>
<P>
Sun, who started her judo career at 14, floored her Cuban peer
Estela Rodriguez, runner-up in the Barcelona Olympics, by Yuk/Isn.
</P>
<P>
German Johanna Hagn and French Christine Cicot shared the
bronze medal in the first event of the judo tournament in the
Games.
</P>
<P>
"I was very calm during the competitions because I know I am
stronger than any of my opponents," Sun, a native of Chinese
northeast province of Liaoning, told the reporter after the final.
</P>
<P>
Sun, 22, suffered a blow in the 1995 Fukuaka Universiade when
she made her first apperance in international arena, by home
judoka Noriko Anno in the semifinal due to lack of experience.
</P>
<P>
After the defeat, Sun started her intensive training in last
July with almost six hours in four periods daily at Tianjin to
gear up for the Centennial Olympic Games.
</P>
<P>
The Chinese budding judoka even tested her prowess by competing
against her men compatriots in the camp, saying that strong mental
merits also play an important role in the competitions.
</P>
<P>
The first-day judo competitions also witnessed the fall of
Angelique Seriese of the Netherlands, champion in the 1995 world
championship, in the first round against German Johanna Hagn,
bronze medalist in Atlanta.
</P>
<P>
And Japanese Anno who won over Sun in the Universiade, also
suffered a first round defeat to Brazilian Edinanci Da Silva.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19960721.0165 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1996-07-21 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Welfare Legislation in Current Form Unacceptable: Official </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, July 20 (Xinhua) -- Welfare reform legislation
being debated in the Senate is unacceptable to President Bill
Clinton in its current form, a White House official said today.
</P>
<P>
Clinton, who promised drastic welfare system reform, vetoed two
previous Republican bills, calling them either too harsh on the
poor or attached to other unacceptable legislation.
</P>
<P>
He had been more positive about the current legislation, but
White House spokesman Mike McCurry said later today, "The welfare
bill as it stands is unacceptable."
</P>
<P>
The Senate rejected a measure Friday that would have changed
the Republican welfare plan to allow children to continue
receiving some federal help after their parents are cut off after
five years on welfare.
</P>
<P>
The Senate vote came on the second day of debate on a
Republican overhaul plan that would replace the nation's various
welfare programs with a single block grant, giving states more say
over the ways to spend the money. The House of Representatives
approved its plan Thursday.
</P>
<P>
Republicans want to end the federal guarantee of aid to the
poor, which has been in place for six decades. Under the plans,
welfare recipients would be required to find jobs within 24 months
of joining the program, and most participants would be cut off
after time limits.
</P>
<P>
States would have the option of denying federal money to
mothers who have more children while on welfare, according to the
plan.
</P>
<P>
Republicans said their plans would free the needy from a cycle
of dependence, restore their dignity and save the country nearly
60 billion dollars over six years. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
