<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Russia Takes First Fencing Gold in Olympics </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ATLANTA, July 20 (Xinhua) -- The first fencing gold medal was
grabbed by Russian Aleksandr Beketov here Saturday afternoon at
the Centennial Olympic Games which raised the curtains Friday
evening.
</P>
<P>
Aleksandr, 26, a warrant officer in the Russian Army, defeated
six opponents en route to his victory of 15-14 over Cuban Ivan
Trevejo Perez, winning the first gold medal for Russia in the
Games.
</P>
<P>
In the breath-taking finals, the two lefthanders chased up in a
tit-for-tat battles all the way to 6-all before the Cuban scored
four hits in a row for a temporary edge of 10-6.
</P>
<P>
By keeping deaf to the cheers of Cubans from the stands,
Beketov, who won the World Cup tournament in Tallin, Estonia early
this year, managed to tie 11-all, 13-all and 14-all before beating
his opponent with the last winning hit with three seconds remained
in the second bout.
</P>
<P>
The bronze medal was won by Geza Imre of Hungary who defeated
compatriot Ivan Kovacs 15-9.
</P>
<P>
The first-day competitions were full of upsets with Eric Srecki
of France, reigning world and Olympic champion, being knocked out
of the top eight by the eventual champion in the third round.
</P>
<P>
Sandro Cuomo of Italy, who placed third at the 1995 worlds,
suffered his defeat to Hungarian Imre in the quarterfinals, with
Arnd Schmitt of Germany, the 1993 world runner-up, being pulled
down by Cuban Perez in the third round.
</P>
<P>
At the 1995 world championship at Hague, the Netherlands, the
Russian fencer only finished fifth in the same event.
</P>
<P>
Started fencing at the age of 13, Beketov, married to Lyudmila
Berketova in 1989 and had his son Denis in 1991, has been coached
by A. Motaev of CSKA Moscow since 1995. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19960721.0176 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1996-07-21 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Mutlu Wins First Weightlifting Gold at Olympics </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ATLANTA, July 20 (Xinhua) -- World recorder holder Halil Mutlu
of Turkey claimed the first gold medal in weightlifting at the
Centennial Olympics with 287.5 kilograms here Saturday afternoon.
</P>
<P>
The hercules, with three records in hands, defeated world
champion Zhang Xiangsen of China for the title, lifting the weight
from 132.5 kilograms in snatch and 155 in jerk in the 54-kg
category.
</P>
<P>
His lift in snatch also set a new world record, 2.5 kilograms
more than the previous one set by himself at the 1994 World
Championships.
</P>
<P>
Zhang Xiangsen, who beat Mutlu at the championships in
Guangzhou last year, had 130 from snatch and 150 from jerk for a
total of 280.
</P>
<P>
Sevdalin Minchev, from Bulgaria, finished third at 277.5, with
125 from snatch and 152.5 from jerk. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
