<HEADLINE> Atlanta ACOG Concerned About Transportation, Technology </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ATLANTA, July 20 (Xinhua) -- The Atlanta Organizing Committee
of Olympic Games (ACOG) expressed great concerns about two issues
of transportation and technology as the 16-day competitions reeled
off today.
</P>
<P>
"We have great concerns on two issues of transportation and
technology" for the Games, said the ACOG spokesman here Saturday.
</P>
<P>
"Yet, situations will be getting better and better as we're to
take account of the advice from the media," he said.
</P>
<P>
"We lack experiences because it's the first time for us to
organize such a great gathering with the participation of the all
the 197 IOC members," explained Ms. Michele Verdier, IOC director
of the Media and Special Projects.
</P>
<P>
One European reporter complained that the transportation
situation here for the Games "was even worse than getting out of
the hell of the Vietnam War".
</P>
<P>
By saying so, the reporter may only intend to raise the proper
attention of ACOG, but the issue of transportation has been
plaguing every participant in the highly-hailed sport gala.
</P>
<P>
"Although we have enough stock, but experienced train drivers
are badly needed here," said the spokesman.
</P>
<P>
On the technology issue, he said staff members of the ACOG will
spare no efforts to put in data, starting lists, results as soon
as possible, saying "wWe will have them done by today."
</P>
<P>
Up till now, reporters were being trapped in a dire situation
when they couldn't retrieve even the starting lists of the sport
wherein the first gold medal has already been won by Renata Mauer
of Poland in the women's 10-meter air rifle. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
