<HEADLINE> Singaporean FM Urges Nuclear-Free Zone in Southeast Asia </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JAKARTA, July 20 (Xinhua) -- Singaporean Foreign Minister
Shanmugam Jayakumar said here today that the Southeast Asian
Nuclear Weapon-Free Zone would promote the peace and stability of
the region.
</P>
<P>
Speaking at the Ministerial Meeting (AMM) of the Association of
Southeast Asian Nations (ASEAN), Jayakumar said the great powers
that had an impact on the peace and security of the region aspired
to become the region's talking partners.
</P>
<P>
India, China and Russia's presence at the annual Post
Ministerial Conference had added to the bloc's responsibility.
</P>
<P>
The two-day AMM is attended by foreign ministers from the seven
ASEAN member countries -- Brunei, Indonesia, Malaysia, the
Philippines, Singapore, Thailand and Vietnam -- as well as its
four observers, Cambodia, Loas, Myanmar and Papua New Guinea.
</P>
