<DATE_TIME> 1996-07-20 16:38 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> UN Report: AIDS Affects World Human Development </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ABU DHABI, July 20 (Xinhua) -- A U.N. report published today in
Abu Dhabi, the capital of the United Arab Emirates (UAE), warned
that the spread of the acquired immune deficiency syndrome (AIDS)
is affecting the human development worldwide, especially in
developing countries.
</P>
<P>
The U.N. Development Program pointed out in the report that it
is developing nations that suffer most from the killer disease.
</P>
<P>
According to the report, 6,000 new AIDS infections occur every
day in the world, that is one in every 15 seconds.
</P>
<P>
The report said that 90 percent of the new infections occur in
developing countries, describing this as a social, economic and
health tragedy.
</P>
<P>
Researches conducted by the program at the University of
Colombia and the Harvard Institute for Human Development showed
that the AIDS virus affects human development and man's essential
abilities, the report said.
</P>
<P>
The report estimated that human development in Asia,
particularly in India and Thailand, would suffer more as a result
of the spread of AIDS there.
</P>
<P>
The report called on governments to cope with the danger of
AIDS more seriously because of its harmful effects on
human development. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
