<HEADLINE> Record-breaking Belgian Swimmer Eyes Gold Medal </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ATLANTA, July 20 (Xinhua) -- Little-known Fred Deburghgraeve
from Belgium who created a new world record in the men's 100m
breaststroke heats here Saturday morning, said he was confident to
win the final this evening.
</P>
<P>
The 23-year-old lanky boy from Roeselare shattered won his heat
race with a time of 1:00.60, shedding 0.35 seconds off the old
mark set by Karoly Guttler of Hungary in Sheffield on August 3,
1993.
</P>
<P>
"It shocked me too. I knew that I could enter tonight's final.
I knew I was able to do that. But a world mark is a surprise for
me," he said.
</P>
<P>
The Belgian was previously a water polo player and he began to
learn swimming at the age of 8.
</P>
<P>
Surprisingly, he had no swimming coach. He trained with his
father Freddiy Deburghgraeve.
</P>
<P>
"Or I'd say my father is my coach and for the most of the time
I train lonely," he said.
</P>
<P>
"I always train at noon, though it's hard," he explained.
</P>
<P>
This is his second appearance in the Olympic pool.
</P>
<P>
His experience in the Barcelona Games in 1992 was painful. He
slipped from the starting blocks and failed to qualify for the
final in the men's 100m breaststroke.
</P>
<P>
He pocketed a bronze medal at the Rome World Championships in
1994.
</P>
<P>
"I think he will do better in tonight's final," his father
said.
</P>
<P>
"If he could win a gold medal in the final, he will become the
first swimmer from Belgium to win an Olympic title," the older
Deburghgraeve added.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
