<HEADLINE> More AIDS Patients Found in Ethiopia </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ADDIS ABABA, July 20 (Xinhua) -- The number of AIDS patients
is rising in the northeast African country of Ethiopia.
</P>
<P>
A report from the Ethiopian News Agency said today, blood
tests made on 817 patients in three hospitals of Central Tigray
and East Wolega zones proved 509 HIV positive.
</P>
<P>
It means that 62 percent of the blood-tested patients will be
AIDS patients. In Axum and Adwa hospitals, the number of HIV
carriers increased by 30 percent than that of the previous year.
</P>
<P>
The report said, most of the patients are civil servants,
drivers, prostitutes and ex-servicemen, adding that the minimal
use of condoms and failure to change one's sexual behaviors have
exposed civil servants and youngsters aged between 15 and 35 to
sexually transmitted diseases.
</P>
<P>
The Ethiopian National AIDS Control Department disclosed
recently that there are about 350,000 actual AIDS cases in the
country presently.
</P>
<P>
A result is that 16-17 percent of the national hospital beds
are occupied by AIDS patients while in the capital, 30-40 percent
of the hospital beds are occupied by AIDS patients and HIV
related victims. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
