<DOCNO> XIE19960721.0193 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1996-07-21 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> France Aims to Take Over NATO's Southern Command: </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PARIS, July 20 (Xinhua) -- France is aiming to take over the
Naples-based Southern Command of the NATO, one year after its
re-entry into NATO's integrated commanding structure, said a
report by the local daily Le Monde today.
</P>
<P>
The report, written by the daily's military correspondent
Jacques Isnard, said that France's participation in U.N. and NATO
peace-keeping forces in former Yugoslavia has "precipitated" the
re-integration of French troops with their allies.
</P>
<P>
In the past 30 years, France has chosen to stay out of the
decision-making structure of NATO since General Charles de Gaulle
withdrew from the NATO caucus dominated by the United States.
</P>
<P>
"Today, in the military circle, people no longer conceal their
willingness to take up actual responsibilities, on condition that
NATO revises its doctrines and missions, and reorganize its
organization and its means to take into account the new strategic
context in Europe after the fall of the Berlin Wall," said the
report.
</P>
<P>
By radically reforming its armed forces, France is also
readjusting to the need of NATO to meet crises and take rapid
actions by streamlining the army into an entity made up of four
groups of forces -- an armored force, a motorized force, an
armored rapid intervention force and an assault infantry force,
with each force manned by 15,000 officers and men.
</P>
<P>
France has declared that a new commanding center for its ground
force will be set up in Lille. The center, called Commandement
Operationnel des Forces Terrestres (COFT), will be equipped with
600-800 cadres and is authorized to command the four groups of
forces, said the report.
</P>
<P>
The COFT will be headed by General Jean Heinrich, a 56-year-old
four-star general who was once head of special operation forces
under the General Direction of Exterior Security and the founder
of the Direction of Military Intelligence, and is number two of
the multinational force in Bosnia.
</P>
<P>
NATO's Northern Command is based in High Wycombe, Britain, and
its Central Command in Brunssum, the Netherlands. Its Southern
Command has been headed by U.S. generals for years. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
