<HEADLINE> New Riot Erupts in N. Ireland </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, July 20 (Xinhua) -- New riot erupted in Northern
Ireland today after nationalist and loyalist parades went ahead,
according to reports from Belfast, capital of Northern Ireland.
</P>
<P>
Around 200 people attacked police with stones and bottles in
the town of Omagh, which lies west of Belfast. They smashed
property and set fire to buildings.
</P>
<P>
The nationalists who want a united Ireland and Protestants who
want the province to stay British held rival parades in the town
Friday night and the rioting began early this morning.
</P>
<P>
To prevent the riot out of control, police fired plastic
bullets and made several arrests. Police said they were not aware
of any more parades planned today, but a nationalist protest over
last week's Protestant march is expected Sunday.
</P>
<P>
The incident was the first serious clash since last week's
widespread street violence in Belfast and Londonderry.
</P>
<P>
Police in England made several arrests this week, seizing
enough equipment to make 36 bombs and documents in what they said
was part of their fight against the Irish Republican Army (IRA).
</P>
<P>
Britain and Ireland called Thursday for a big push in next
week's peace talks between the various parties in Northern
Ireland, to reestablish what the governments called "the primacy of
politics" over violence.
</P>
<P>
However, one of the key players, Sinn Fein, the political wing
of the IRA, has been excluded because the IRA broke a 17-month
cease-fire in February and has launched bomb attacks in mainland
Britain.
</P>
<P>
Political observers here believe that the peace talks can hardly
achieve any result without Sinn Fein's taking part in.
</P>
<P>
"Confidence in the ability of the talks process to deliver
meaningful change has already disappeared," Sinn Fein President
Gerry Adams said Friday. 
</P>
</TEXT>
