<DATE_TIME> 1996-07-20 18:38 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Israel,Hezbollah to Swap Soldiers' Remains </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIRUT, July 20 (Xinhua) -- Israel and Lebanon's Hezbollah are
to carry out a deal of swapping the remains of two Israeli
soldiers for Lebanese prisoners and bodies of guerrillas on
Sunday morning, well-informed Hezbollah sources said here
tonight.
</P>
<P>
Israel will release 45 prisoners from a jail at Khiam deeply
inside the Israeli self-proclaimed "security zone" in southern
Lebanon,
</P>
<P>
The prisoners will be transferred by the International Red
Cross Committee (IRCC) through the Fart Mnita crossing point northward
to the southern Lebanese market town of Nabatiyeh, according to
Red Cross sources.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, 14 Red Cross vehicles will transport 123 bodies of
Shiite Moslem guerrillas from inside Israel, and 18 bodies from
the Israeli-occupied border strip, to Nabatiyeh, then to a mosque
on Beirut's southern suburbs.
</P>
<P>
At 7:30 a.m. (04:30 GMT), a helicopter is to take off from the
Beirut International Airport, lifting the remains of two Israeli
soldiers and two elements of Israeli-backed South Lebanon Army
(SLA) militia to Cyprus.
</P>
<P>
Seventeen SLA militiamen to be set free by the pro-Iranian
Hezbollah, or Party of God, will be repatriated by the same
helicopter.
</P>
<P>
Bernd Schmidbauer, German minister of state for security
affairs, will fly to the Beirut airport early Sunday morning
from Damascus to pick up the remains and SLA prisoners.
</P>
<P>
At the end of the repatriation, the German official, who is
also a top intelligence adviser to Chancellor Helmut Kohl, will
hold a press conference to talk on details of the operation,
reliable official sources said on condition of anonymity.
</P>
<P>
Schmidbauer was sent by his government to broker the deal
among Lebanon, Israel and Syria.
</P>
<P>
The Hezbollah sources said that the Red Cross convoy carrying
the guerrillas bodies and the prisoners will stop around 9:30
a.m. (06:30 GMT) in front of the office of a Hezbollah
parliamentary member, Mohammed Raad, in Nabatiyeh.
</P>
<P>
Philipe Gayar, IRCC's top representative in Lebanon, announced
in Beirut today that the parties concerned in Lebanon, Israel and
Germany had contacted the international organization to seek help
in carrying out the operation.
</P>
<P>
He said that the committee had prepared vehicles for this
purpose.
</P>
<P>
After meeting the German mediator in Damascus, Hezbollah's
Secretary General Sheikh Hassan Nasrallah announced that his
party had endorsed the swap deal which is to be executed on
Sunday.
</P>
<P>
He described the German-brokered agreement as "an advancing
step on the road to a solution of the problem facing all the
prisoners held by Israel, the most prominent of whom are Sheikh
Abdel Karim Abeid and Mostafa Dirani."
</P>
<P>
Abeid and Dirani were abducted from their homes by Israeli
commandos in 1989 and 1994 respectively.
</P>
<P>
Israel said that the two Hezbollah leaders would not be
released until it finds out what had happened to four other
Israeli military servicemen missing in southern Lebanon since
1986, including air force pilot Ron Arad. Israel believes Arad is
still alive.
</P>
<P>
Nasrallah stressed that the fate of Arad and other missing
Israeli soldiers "constitutes a big obstacle to a full solution."
</P>
<P>
At a press conference in the Syrian capital today, Schmidbauer
thanked Syria and Iran for contributions that crowned his mission
with success.
</P>
<P>
Lebanon's government insists that the operation of swap should
be conducted under its supervision.
</P>
<P>
"The exchange will be completed with the government's
knowledge and under its supervision and by the goodwill efforts
of the German government which sent Minister Schmidbauer to
contact with all the parties," said Interior Minister Michel
Al-Murr Friday. 
</P>
</TEXT>
