<HEADLINE> No More Obstacles to Elections on Bosnian Serb Side: </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BELGRADE, July 20 (Xinhua) -- Bosnian Serb state Republika
Srpska Acting President Biljana Plavsic said today there were no
more obstacles to elections after Serb leader Radovan Karadzic
withdrew from the political scene.
</P>
<P>
Plavsic told the local radio in the central Serbian town of
Jagodina that she had said this to head of the Bosnia mission of
the Organization for Security and Cooperation in Europe (OSCE)
Robert Frowick, to which he had agreed.
</P>
<P>
Under the Dayton agreement, the OSCE is charged with organizing
and monitoring the first post-war elections in Bosnia in
September.
</P>
<P>
Plavsic said that Karadzic's handing over of the state and
political offices was a "rational move, which was not difficult to
implement."
</P>
<P>
Under strong pressure from the West, Karadzic agreed Friday to
relinquish the offices of Republika Srpska president and president
of the Serbian Democratic Party (SDS). Plavsic, who is Republika
Srpska vice president, temporarily took over the first office and
Foreign Minister Aleksa Buha took over the second.
</P>
<P>
Frowick has postponed the election campaign in Bosnia from July
15 till 19 because Karadzic still hang on the presidency of the
SDS. Bosnian Muslim leaders also threatened to boycott the voting
if Karadzic did not step down and disappear from the public life.
</P>
<P>
Plavsic said she believed that Frowick was a "determined man,
who knows what he wants" and that he would allow no "manipulations
by the Muslim-Croat federation," which had serious problems and
wished to blame them on Republika Srpska.
</P>
<P>
"Our people who contact Frowick's associates are very satisfied
with their cooperation and I heard that his people were satisfied
with our cooperation and I really expect a fair way to the
elections," Plavsic said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
