<HEADLINE> Israeli Police Clash with Religious Demonstrators </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, July 20 (Xinhua) -- Israeli police clashed here
Saturday with ultra-orthodox demonstrators who tried to block a
downtown street to traffic on the Jewish sabbath.
</P>
<P>
Thousands of angry black-clad demonstrators threw stones at
police and passing cars on the Ban-Ilan Street in an
ultra-orthodox neighborhood.
</P>
<P>
Hundreds of policemen used water-cannon to disperse the big
crowd, while mounted police tried time and again to push the
demonstrators back.
</P>
<P>
Hundred yards away, a counter-demonstration was held by secular
groups led by the left-wing Meretz party, which have been
campaigning for free passing on the arterial road even on the
Sabbath.
</P>
<P>
They asserted that the road also serves thousands of secular
residents in surrounding districts as well as a major city hospital.
</P>
<P>
The police said that three of the ultra-orthodox demonstrators
were arrested for throwing stones. No injury was reported during
the clash.  
