<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Sudan Confirms Commitment to "Artery of Life" Deal </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KHARTOUM, July 20 (Xinhua) -- Sudan's Foreign Ministry today
confirmed in a statement that the Sudanese government will commit
to the "artery of life" deal signed between Sudan and the U.N. in
1989.
</P>
<P>
The statement voiced the government's willingness to cooperate
with the U.N. and the international community for enabling the
residents of southern Sudan to obtain relief goods.
</P>
<P>
The ministry also expressed astonishment and regret at a
U.N. report indicating that the Sudanese government was hindering
the delivery of relief supplies to the war-torn south.
</P>
<P>
Last September, Sudan barred the U.N. World Food Program from
using C-130 transport planes to deliver food to the south, where
Christian and animist rebels have been battling the northern
Moslem-dominated Khartoum government since 1983.
</P>
<P>
On July 12, World Food Program officials told reporters in New
York that the Sudanese government's restrictions on international
food aid have put 700,000 people at risk of starvation in the
south.
</P>
<P>
The Sudanese government was reportedly to have claimed that
humanitarian groups have used planes to smuggle weapons to
southern rebels.
</P>
<P>
However, the United Nations and other organizations have
strongly denied the allegation. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
