<HEADLINE> ANC to Step Up Cooperation With PAC, Mandela Says </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, July 20 (Xinhua) -- South African President
Nelson Mandela said today steps are being taken towards more
cooperation between the Pan Africanist Congress (PAC) and the
African National Congress (ANC).
</P>
<P>
Addressing about 1000 anti-apartheid veterans celebrating his
birthday in Pretoria, Mandela said those who fought in the
liberation movements should enjoy together the "fruits of the
liberation".
</P>
<P>
Mandela said PAC leader Clarence Makwetu has declined four
offers to join the government of national unity.
</P>
<P>
PAC, established in April 1954, is one of the major political
organizations fighting against the anti-apartheid system.
</P>
<P>
"We must let the smaller parties feel that they are part and
parcel of decision making," said the president, adding minority
parties should not be allowed to become rubber stamps for the
ANC.
</P>
<P>
Mandela also warned of the danger of government officials
promoting their own interests and forgetting those of the people
who had elected them.
</P>
<P>
Referring to criticism of the government, Mandela said
although the ANC-led government wants to better the lives of all
South Africans, this is not something that could be done
overnight. 
</P>
</TEXT>
