<HEADLINE> Yugoslavia Beats Greece in Basketball Opening Game </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ATLANTA, June 20 (Xinhua) -- European champion Yugoslavia won a
tough game by beating the pesky Greece 71-63 in 37 minutes here on
Saturday in the opening match of the men's basketball competition
at the 26th Olympic Games.
</P>
<P>
Greece, in their first Olympic appearance in the men's
basketball, held to a 58-56 lead by their opponents with 3:27
munites remaining before Dejan Bodiroga sunk a three-pointer to
start the rally for Yugoslavia.
</P>
<P>
The Yugoslavians scored 15 points to assure their victory while
their opponents only managed to five points.
</P>
<P>
"Our players gave their very best performance, but
unfortunately the more experienced Yugoslavians were able to
survive in the last few minutes," said Greek head coach Makis
Dedrinos.
</P>
<P>
"Their last three or four attacks gave them the advantage. In
return, we were not able to progress the points," Dedrinos added.
</P>
<P>
The Yugoslavians took a comfortable lead of 10-2 and carried
the edge 41-35 before the Greeks making a come back by scoring
eight points in a raw to go up 43-41.
</P>
<P>
"Yugoslavia's starting center Vlade Divac, recently traded by
his NBA team -- the Los Angeles Lakers to the Charlotte Hornets,
was held to just six points with early fauls problems, but the
2.12-meter NBA veteran was realy strong in defence with eight
rebounders.
</P>
<P>
"It's always slow and the first game is always like that," said
Vivac, who joined the LA Lakers in 1988.
</P>
<P>
Predrag Danilovic, another Yugoslavian NBA player with the
Miami Heat, said:"It was a hard game, and we were nervous. It was
what we expected because we played a game for a while."
</P>
<P>
The two sides tied at 30-30 at the end of the first half, after
Predrag Danilovic of Yugoslavia and Theofanis Christodoulou of
Greece each hit back-to-back three pointer in the last 27 seconds.
</P>
<P>
Zoran Savic led Yugoslavia with 21 points, followed by
Danilovic with 16. Greece was led by Panayotis Fassoulas with 21
points and 10 rebounds.
</P>
<P>
Earlier in the morning, Australia routed South Korea 111-88 in
a lop-sided match. The taller and stronger Australians led the
first half 64-37.
</P>
<P>
Andrew Gaze scored a game high 26 points to lead six
Australians finished in double figures while June Jae-Kun hit 23
for South Korea, followed by Moon Kyung-Eun with 17. 
</P>
</TEXT>
