<HEADLINE> Perot, Lamm Speak to Reform Party Faithfuls </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, July 20 (Xinhua) -- Reform Party founder Ross Perot
and former Governor Richard Lamm of Colorado of the United States,
both seeking the Reform Party's presidential nomination, spoke to
the party faithfuls today.
</P>
<P>
Perot, taking the state party convention stage in
Charlottesville, Virginia, after Lamm in their first shared public
appearance, promised to "do better" than Republican and Democratic
leaders if he were president of the United States.
</P>
<P>
"If you make me your candidate, I will dedicate myself as a
servant to the American people -- bought, paid for and owned by
the American people," media reports quoted Perot as saying.
</P>
<P>
Perot, who for months had said he no longer coveted the
presidency, announced his candidacy on July 10 -- one day after
Lamm, a lifelong Democrat, said he would run.
</P>
<P>
Lamm said, "America desperately needed a new political party,
desperately needed a new political movement that was dedicated to
reform and renewal of America."
</P>
<P>
Perot said the Reform Party had "a game plan." "We've got
strategy and tactics and we've got 62 percent of the voters who
want a new political party and with all of that if we do our job
right we can win," he said.
</P>
<P>
Lamm said the party would not take money from political action
committees, but would support itself on mall contributions.
</P>
<P>
Recalling the budget battles last year and the government
shutdowns, Perot said, "We don't need any more government
shutdowns."
</P>
<P>
"We don't need fights in the House of Representatives. We don't
need stunts and train wrecks.... We need careful, thoughtful,
rational action to get the job done," he said.
</P>
<P>
Perot also sent a message to congressional candidates, saying,
"We must win the presidency and this is just as important or even
more important, we're going to endorse the candidates in every
House and Senate race across this country who are committed to
reform and we can provide the swing vote to put about 100 percent
of them in office." 
</P>
</TEXT>
