<HEADLINE> Zeng, First Chinese Male Swimmer into the Olympic Final </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ATLANTA, July 20 (Xinhua) -- Zeng Qiliang from South China's
Guangdong Province finally fulfilled the dream for all his fellow
Chinese male swimmers: to book a berth in the Olympic finals.
</P>
<P>
The 21-year-old Chinese clocked a time of one minute 2.26
seconds to finish eighth after the preliminaries, which ensured
him a berth in tonight's final.
</P>
<P>
Born on May 10, 1975, the 1.73-meter high Zeng had no advantage
physically, but he struggled to cross the finish-line with strong
strokes.
</P>
<P>
Before the Olympic Games, China had set a modest goal for their
male swimmers: just to make the final. In fact, Zeng had done it
well and no matter win or lose tonight in the final, he will
surely be written into the Chinese swimming almanac.
</P>
<P>
Chen Yan, 16, who clocked a year's best time of 4:40.85 in the
400m individual medley, clocked a slow time of 4:53.87 and was
eliminated from the final.
</P>
<P>
Chen claimed a total of four golds and one bronze out of five
events she entered at the Chinese Olympic trials in Tianjing last
April.
</P>
<P>
Another Chinese teenager Wu Yanyan, from south China's Guangxi
Province, who clocked the year's best time in the 200m individual
medley, was also edged out from the final. 
</P>
</TEXT>
