<HEADLINE> World Court Nominates Arbitrator for Controversial </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BELGRADE, July 20 (Xinhua) -- The International Court of
Justice has nominated U.S. lawyer Roberts Owen as the third
arbitrator in a territorial dispute over Brcko in northeastern
Bosnia.
</P>
<P>
This was announced by Colum Murphy, spokesman for the
international High Representative for Bosnia Carl Bildt at a news
conference in Sarajevo today, reports from the Bosnian capital
said.
</P>
<P>
Owen, one Bosnian Serb and one Bosnian Muslim arbitrator should
decide in the dispute over a corridor which links the eastern and
western parts of the Bosnian Serb state of Republika Srpska. Both
the Serbs and the Muslims claim that Brcko, a strategic town,
belong to them.
</P>
<P>
"We do not expect a speedy solution, because the issue is very
sensitive and complex," Murphy said. He expressed the hope that
the first meeting of the three arbitrators would take place
Monday, if a venue could be agreed upon.
</P>
<P>
Reports said the international court had intervened after
Republika Srpska and the Muslim government failed to agree on the
third arbitrator within a deadline set under the Dayton peace
agreement.
</P>
<P>
Brcko, a still controversial place in Bosnia, will be decided
by international arbitration within a year after the Dayton
agreement was signed last December. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
