<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Bosnian Serbs Accuse NATO Planes of Dropping Chemicals </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BELGRADE, July 20 (Xinhua) -- The Civil Defense Department in
Doboj, a Serb town in northern Bosnia, accused today NATO planes
of dropping large quantities of chemicals hazardous for the
population and environment.
</P>
<P>
The Civil Defense Department said in a statement that by
dropping suffocating chemicals, NATO planes and helicopters were
"spreading panic among local population" for quite some time.
</P>
<P>
It was not known whether the chemicals were dropped
accidentally or for other reasons. But a previous report on
unknown and health hazardous agents dropped by NATO planes Monday
was denied by the command of the Nordic-Polish Brigade of the
peace Implementation Force (IFOR) in Doboj.
</P>
<P>
The Yugoslav Tanjug news agency quoted the statement as saying
that the latest cases were registered when two NATO planes
overflew Doboj and its surroundings Monday and NATO helicopters
flew over the region of Mt. Ozren Friday.
</P>
<P>
After several NATO plane overflights, "citizens sought help in
Doboj emergency medical institutions, complaining about heavy
breathing, throat tickling, headaches, vomiting, cough and
fatigue," the statement said.
</P>
<P>
It added that after the chemicals were dropped, many pigs,
calves and other domestic animals died and other negative effects
were registered on fruit trees, crops and in forests.
</P>
<P>
Tanjug also reported that a 230-kg bomb accidentally fell off a
U.S. NATO plane this afternoon and exploded in the southeast of
the northern Bosnian town of Brcko.
</P>
<P>
No one was injured in the explosion, which took place in an
open area on the edge of a U.S. base, just inside the Muslim-Croat
federation, NATO spokesman Col. Max Marriner said in Sarajevo.
</P>
<P>
According to initial reports, there was no damage and an
investigation is under way, Marriner added. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
